title: Bootstrapping Estimators based on the Block Maxima Method

sections.text:
#### Abstract

The block maxima method is a standard approach for analyzing the extremal behavior of a potentially multivariate time series. It has recently been found that the classical approach based on disjoint block maxima may be universally improved by considering sliding block maxima instead. However, the asymptotic variance formula for estimators based on sliding block maxima involves an integral over the covariance of a certain family of multivariate extreme value distributions, which makes its estimation, and inference in general, an intricate problem. As an alternative, one may rely on bootstrap approximations: we show that naive block-bootstrap approaches from time series analysis are inconsistent even in i.i.d. situations, and provide a consistent alternative based on resampling circular block maxima. As a by-product, we show consistency of the classical resampling bootstrap for disjoint block maxima, and that estimators based on circular block maxima have the same asymptotic variance as their sliding block maxima counterparts. The finite sample properties are illustrated by Monte Carlo experiments, and the methods are demonstrated by a case study of precipitation extremes.


Keywords. Bootstrap Consistency; Disjoint and Sliding Block Maxima; Extreme Value Statistics; Pseudo Maximum Likelihood Estimation; Time Series Analysis.

# 1. Introduction 

A common approach to statistically assess extreme events is the block maxima method. For block size $r \in \mathbb{N}$, for instance $r=365$ corresponding to a year of daily observations, its starting point is the vector $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}=\max _{t=1}^{r} \boldsymbol{X}_{t}=\left(\max _{t=1}^{r} X_{t 1}, \ldots, \max _{t=1}^{r} X_{t d}\right)^{\top}$ of componentwise maxima over $r$ successive observations from a time series $\left(X_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$ in $\mathbb{R}^{d}$; with $\boldsymbol{X}_{t}=\left(X_{t 1}, \ldots, X_{t d}\right)^{\top}$. In view of a version of the classical extremal types theorem for multivariate time series, the distribution of $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}$ may be approximated by a multivariate extreme value distribution, for sufficiently large block size $r$. Both the distribution of $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}$ and parameters related to its potential weak limit distribution are common target parameters in extreme value statistics, with applications in finance, insurance or environmental statistics among others (Beirlant et al., 2004; Katz et al., 2002). For instance, in extreme event attribution studies (e.g., for cumulative daily precipitation amounts), one is typically interested in specific large quantiles or exeedance probabilities of $M_{365}$ that are defined by a recent observed extreme event. These parameters are directly linked to return levels and return periods of the underlying time series, and allow for assessing the effect of global warming on the observed event, for instance in terms of probability ratios (van Oldenborgh et al., 2017; Philip et al., 2020; Tradowsky et al., 2023).

Figure 1: Empirical distribution of the estimation error and the bootstrap estimation error for 100year return level estimation in Model 6.1 with $\gamma=-0.2, \beta=0.5, m=80, r=365$. Left: naive sliding approach. Right: circular bootstrap approach. See Section 4 and Figure 4 for further details.

Formally, the statistical analysis starts from $\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{n}$, an observed stretch from an (approximately) stationary time series $\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$. The classical block maxima method for estimating quantities associated with the law of $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}$ (or its limiting law for $r \rightarrow \infty$ ) consists of dividing the sampling period $\{1, \ldots, n\}$ into $m$ disjoint blocks of length $r$ (for simplicity, we assume that $n=m r$ ), and of using the (disjoint) block maxima sample $\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{1, r}^{[\mathrm{d}]} \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{m, r}^{[\mathrm{d}]}\right)$ as a starting point for statistical methods; here $\boldsymbol{M}_{t, r}^{[\mathrm{d}]}=\max _{t=(i-1) r+1, \ldots, i r} \boldsymbol{X}_{t}$ denotes the $i$ th disjoint block maximum. This classical approach can often be improved by instead considering the sliding block maxima sample $\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{1, r}^{[s]} \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{n-r+1, r}^{[s]}\right)$ as a starting point; here $\boldsymbol{M}_{t, r}^{[s]}=\max _{t=i, \ldots, i+r-1} \boldsymbol{X}_{t}$ denotes the block maximum of size $r$ starting at "day" $i$. Note that this sample also provides an (approximately) stationary, but strongly auto-correlated sample from the law of $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}$. It was shown in Bücher and Segers (2018a); Zou et al. (2021) among others that estimators that explicitly or implicitly involve empirical means of the sliding block maxima sample typically have the same expectation but a slightly smaller variance than the respective counterparts based on the disjoint block maxima sample.

It seems natural that a lower estimation variance offers the possibility of constructing smaller confidence intervals for a given confidence level, thereby for instance allowing for more precise statements regarding the aforementioned extreme event attribution. The main goal of this work is to find universal practical solutions for this heuristic based on suitable bootstrap approximations. A challenge consists of the fact that the large sample asymptotics of the sliding block maxima method depend on a blocking of blocks approach involving some intermediate blocking parameter converging to infinity at a well-balanced rate. As a consequence, standard bootstrap approaches for time series like the block bootstrap (Lahiri, 2003) would depend on such an intermediate "blocking of blocks" parameter as well (which must be avoided due to the typically small effective sample size in extreme value analysis), while naive approaches based on (blockwise) resampling of sliding block maxima will be inconsistent (see Fig. 1, Remark 4.3 below, and Section D in the supplement). As illustrated on the right-hand side of Fig. 1, a novel approach based on what we call the circular (sliding) block maxima sample allows for consistent distributional approximations without relying on such an intermediate parameter sequence. At the same time, the method is computationally attractive because it avoids recalculation of any block maxima for the bootstrap sample.

In general, various variants of the bootstrap have been routinely applied in extreme value statistics (see, for instance, Eastoe and Tawn, 2008; Huser and Davison, 2014). However, to the best of our knowledge, respective statistical theory is only available for the peak-over-threshold method (Peng and Qi, 2008; Drees, 2015; Davis et al., 2018; Kulik and Soulier, 2020; Jentsch and Kulik, 2021;

de Haan and Zhou, 2024). Concerning the block maxima method, within the regime where the block size is treated as a parameter sequence $r=r_{n}$ converging to infinity, the only reference we are aware of is de Haan and Zhou (2024), who derive an asymptotic expansion for the tail quantile process of bootstrapped disjoint block maxima. However, their results require an underlying IID sequence, they only concern the disjoint block maxima method and they do not eventually imply desirable classical consistency statements. While our main focus is on the sliding block maxima method, we establish consistency results for the disjoint block maxima method as a by-product, for serially dependent data.

Finally, we also derive limit results for empirical means and estimators based on the circular (sliding) block maxima sample, and prove that they show the same favorable asymptotic behavior as the sliding block maxima counterparts. As we will discuss in the conclusion, the result may be of independent interest when dealing with non-stationary situations involving, for example, trends, which is typical for climate extremes.

All methods in this paper are intrinsically linked to the block maxima method. In typical use cases of that method, target parameters directly depend on the block maxima distribution (and hence on $r$ ); it can thus be considered a very natural approach in this situation. When target parameters depend on the marginal distribution of $X_{t}$ (e.g., high quantiles), the peak-over-threshold method is typically considered the more natural and useful approach. As such, both methods have their raison d'être and are most suitable for different applications; see also the discussion in Section 3.3 in Bücher and Zhou (2021).

The remaining parts of this paper are organized as follows: basic model assumptions and known results on the disjoint and sliding block maxima method are collected in Section 2. The sample of circular block maxima is introduced in Section 3 and supplemented by a central limit theorem. Appropriate bootstrap schemes are proposed in Section 4, where we also provide respective consistency statements. The previous high-level results are applied to a specific estimation problem for univariate heavy tailed time series in Section 5. Finite-sample results on a large-scale simulation study and two case studies are presented in Sections 6 and 7, respectively. Section 8 concludes. Some technical integrability and bias conditions are given in Section 9. Finally, all proofs, additional theoretical results and additional simulation results are provided in a supplementary material. The code used for the simulation study is available on Github, see Staud (2024). Throughout, weak convergence of sequences of random vectors/distributions is denoted by $\sim$.

# 2. Mathematical preliminaries 

Throughout this section, we present basic model assumptions rooted in extreme value theory for stationary time series. We then summarize the most important aspects about the (disjoint and sliding) block maxima method, including a central limit theorem (CLT) for sample averages based on affinely standardized block maxima. We also present high level conditions under which the CLTs can be used as a basis for statistical inference and illustrate them with some examples.

### 2.1. Basic model assumptions

An extension of the classical extremal types theorem to strictly stationary time series (Leadbetter, 1983) implies that, under suitable broad conditions, affinely standardized maxima extracted from a stationary time series converge to the generalized extreme value distribution (GEV). This was generalized to the multivariate case in Hsing (1989), where the marginals are necessarily GEV-

distributed. We make this an assumption, and additionally require the scaling sequences to exhibit some common regularity inspired by the max-domain of attraction condition in the IID case (de Haan and Ferreira, 2006).

Condition 2.1 (Multivariate max-domain of attraction). Let $\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$ denote a strictly stationary time series in $\mathbb{R}^{d}$ with continuous margins. There exist sequences $\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}\right)_{r}=\left(a_{r}^{(1)}, \ldots, a_{r}^{(d)}\right)_{r} \subset(0, \infty)^{d},\left(\boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right)_{r}=$ $\left(b_{r}^{(1)}, \ldots, b_{r}^{(d)}\right)_{r} \subset \mathbb{R}^{d}$ and $\boldsymbol{\gamma}=\left(\gamma^{(1)}, \ldots, \gamma^{(d)}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$, such that, for any $s>0$ and $j \in\{1, \ldots, d\}$,

$$
\lim _{r \rightarrow \infty} \frac{a_{[r s]}^{(j)}}{a_{r}^{(j)}}=s^{s^{(j)}}, \quad \lim _{r \rightarrow \infty} \frac{b_{[r s]}^{(j)}-b_{r}^{(j)}}{a_{r}^{(j)}}=\frac{s^{s^{(j)}}-1}{\gamma^{(j)}}
$$

where the second limit is interpreted as $\log (s)$ if $\gamma^{(j)}=0$. Moreover, for $r \rightarrow \infty$,

$$
\boldsymbol{Z}_{r}=\frac{\boldsymbol{M}_{r}-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}}{\boldsymbol{a}_{r}} \rightsquigarrow \boldsymbol{Z} \sim G
$$

where $G$ denotes the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of a $d$-variate extreme-value distribution with marginal CDFs $G_{\gamma^{(1)}}, \ldots, G_{\gamma^{(d)}}$ (with $G_{\gamma}(x)=\exp \left(-(1+\gamma x)^{-1 / \gamma}\right) 1(1+\gamma x>0)$ the CDF of the $\operatorname{GEV}(\gamma)$-distribution) and where division by the vector $\boldsymbol{a}_{r}$ is understood componentwise, that is, $\boldsymbol{Z}_{r}=\left(Z_{r}^{(1)}, \ldots, Z_{r}^{(d)}\right)$ with $Z_{r}^{(j)}=\left\{\max \left(X_{1}^{(j)}, \ldots, X_{r}^{(j)}\right)-b_{r}^{(j)}\right\} / a_{r}^{(j)}$ for $j \in\{1, \ldots, d\}$.

Note that (2.1) and (2.2) may for instance be deduced from Leadbetter's $D\left(u_{\pi}\right)$ condition, a domain-of-attraction condition on the associated IID sequence with stationary distribution equal to that of $\boldsymbol{X}_{0}$ and a weak requirement on the convergence of the CDF of $\boldsymbol{Z}_{r}$, see Theorem 10.22 in Beirlant et al. (2004).

Throughout this paper, we assume to observe $\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{n}$, an excerpt from a $d$-dimensional time series $\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$ satisfying Condition 2.1. Block maxima will be formed with respect to a block size parameter $r=r_{n}$ converging to infinity such that $r=o(n)$. For establishing the subsequent limit results, the serial dependence of $\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t}$ will additionally be controlled via the Rosenblatt mixing coefficient (Bradley, 2005). For two sigma-fields $\mathcal{F}_{1}, \mathcal{F}_{2}$ on a probability space $(\Omega, \mathcal{A}, \mathbb{P})$, let $\alpha\left(\mathcal{F}_{1}, \mathcal{F}_{2}\right)=$ $\sup _{A \in \mathcal{F}_{1}, B \in \mathcal{F}_{2}} \mid \mathbb{P}(A \cap B)-\mathbb{P}(A) \mathbb{P}(B) \mid$. For positive integer $p$, let $\alpha(p):=\alpha\left(\sigma\left(\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t \leq 0}\right), \sigma\left(\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t \geq p}\right)\right)$, with $\sigma(\cdot)$ denoting the sigma-field generated by its argument.

Condition 2.2 (Block size and mixing). The block size sequence $\left(r_{n}\right)_{n}$ satisfies, as $n \rightarrow \infty$ :
(a) $r_{n} \rightarrow \infty$ and $r_{n}=o(n)$.
(b) There exists a sequence $\left(\ell_{n}\right)_{n} \subset \mathbb{N}$ such that $\ell_{n} \rightarrow \infty, \ell_{n}=o\left(r_{n}\right), \frac{r_{n}}{r_{n}} \alpha\left(\ell_{n}\right)=o(1)$, and $\frac{n}{r_{n}} \alpha\left(\ell_{n}\right)=$ $o(1)$.
(c) $\left(\frac{n}{r_{n}}\right)^{1+\omega} \alpha\left(r_{n}\right)=o(1)$ for some $\omega>0$.

# 2.2. Empirical means of rescaled disjoint or sliding block maxima 

A central theoretical ingredient for establishing weak limit results on estimators based on the block maxima method is the weak convergence of either the tail quantile process or of empirical means of (unobservable) rescaled block maxima. Respective results on the former can be found in Theorem 2.1 in Ferreira and de Haan (2015), while the latter approach was taken in Theorems 2.6/B. 1 in Bücher and Zanger (2023), in the proof of Theorem 2.6 in Bücher and Segers (2018a) or in Theorem 2.4 in Zou et al. (2021). Throughout this paper, we also follow the latter approach, and for completeness, we summarize the essence in a theorem and briefly summarize and discuss potential statistical applications.

For $i \in\{1, \ldots, n-r+1\}$, write $\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}=\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{i}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{i+r-1}\right)$, and define $\overline{\mathcal{M}}_{n, r}^{\{d\}}=\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}: i \in I_{n}^{\mathrm{d}}\right)$ and $\overline{\mathcal{M}}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{s}\}}=\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}: i \in I_{n}^{\mathrm{s}}\right)$ as the (vanilla) disjoint and sliding block maxima samples, respectively, where $I_{n}^{\mathrm{d}}=\left\{(i-1) r+1: 1 \leq i \leq n / r\right\}$ and $I_{n}^{\mathrm{s}}=\{1, \ldots, n-r+1\}$. We are interested in the associated empirical measures $n_{\mathrm{m}}^{-1} \sum_{i \in I_{n}^{\mathrm{m}}} \delta_{\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}}$, or their versions based on rescaled block maxima $n_{\mathrm{m}}^{-1} \sum_{i \in I_{n}^{\mathrm{m}}} \delta_{\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right) / \boldsymbol{a}_{r}}$, with $n_{\mathrm{m}}=\left|I_{n}^{\mathrm{m}}\right|$ and $\delta_{\mathrm{z}}$ the Dirac-measure at $\boldsymbol{z}$. The fact that the sample size $n_{\mathrm{m}}$ depends on m is a notational nuisance which we subsequently resolve by the following asymptotically negligible modification: first, the disjoint block maxima sample may be identified with the sample $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{d}\}}=\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, 1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{r, 1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{r, n / r}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{r, n / r}\right)$ of size $n$ containing each disjoint block maximum exactly $r$ times; note that the respective empirical measures of $\overline{\mathcal{M}}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{d}\}}$ and $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{d}\}}$ are the same. Next, we define $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{s}\}}$ as the sliding block maxima sample of size $n$ calculated from the extended sample $\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{n}, \boldsymbol{X}_{n+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{n+r-1}\right)$. In the subsequent asymptotic results, this modification is asymptotically negligible since the first $n-r+1$ maxima in $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{s}\}}$ are exactly the maxima in $\overline{\mathcal{M}}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{s}\}}$. These modifications allow to define $\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, 1}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{r, n}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}\right):=\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}$, and using the notation $\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, i}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}:=\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right) / \boldsymbol{a}_{r}$, we define

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}-P_{r}\right), \quad \mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}-P\right)
$$

where $\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} \delta_{\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, i}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}}, P_{r}=\mathbb{P}\left(\boldsymbol{Z}_{r} \in\right.$. $)$ and $P=\mathbb{P}(\boldsymbol{Z} \in)$. Finally, let

$$
G_{\xi}(\boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{y})=G(\boldsymbol{x})^{\xi \wedge 1} G(\boldsymbol{y})^{\xi \wedge 1} G(\boldsymbol{x} \wedge \boldsymbol{y})^{1-(\xi \wedge 1)}, \quad \boldsymbol{x}, \boldsymbol{y} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}
$$

and note that $G_{\xi}$ is a $2 d$-variate extreme-value distribution; see Formula (3.8) and its discussion in Bücher and Staud (2024) for further details. The following result relies on some suitable integrability and bias conditions (Conditions 9.1 and 9.2), which are postponed to Section 9 in the appendix for presentation reasons.

Theorem 2.3. Under Conditions 2.1 and 2.2, for any finite set of real valued functions $h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}$ satisfying the integrability Condition 9.1(a) with $v>2 / \omega$ where $\omega$ is from Condition 2.2, we have, writing $\boldsymbol{h}=\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}$,

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}} \boldsymbol{h}=\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}} h_{1}, \ldots, \hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}} h_{q}\right)^{\top} \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{q}\left(\mathbf{0}, \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}\right), \quad \mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{~d}, \mathrm{~s}\}
$$

where

$$
\left(\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[d]}\right)_{j, j^{\prime}=1}^{q}=\operatorname{Cov}\left(h_{j}(\boldsymbol{Z}), h_{j^{\prime}}(\boldsymbol{Z})\right), \quad\left(\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[s]}\right)_{j, j^{\prime}=1}^{q}=2 \int_{0}^{1} \operatorname{Cov}\left(h_{j}\left(Z_{1, \xi}\right), h_{j^{\prime}}\left(Z_{2, \xi}\right)\right) \mathrm{d} \xi
$$

with $\boldsymbol{Z} \sim G$ from Condition 2.1 and $\left(\boldsymbol{Z}_{1, \xi}, \boldsymbol{Z}_{2, \xi}\right) \sim G_{\xi}$ from (2.3). Moreover, $\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[s]} \leq_{L} \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[d]}$, where $\leq_{L}$ denotes the Loewner ordering. Finally, if the bias Condition 9.2 holds, then

$$
\mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}} \boldsymbol{h}=\left(\mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}} h_{1}, \ldots, \mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}} h_{q}\right)^{\top} \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{q}\left(\boldsymbol{B}_{\boldsymbol{h}}, \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{\{\mathrm{m}\}}\right)
$$

In statistical applications, one is typically interested in distributional approximations for the estimation error of general statistics depending on the observable block maxima $\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}$ (here and in the following, we omit the superscript ' $m$ '). As discussed in the following remark, such approximations can be deduced from Theorem 2.3.
Remark 2.4 (Normal approximations for statistics depending on observable block maxima). Suppose that $\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}=\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, 1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{r, n}\right)$ is some estimator of interest for a target parameter $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$ (with

$p \in \mathbb{N}$ ), where $\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}$ is a measurable function on $\left(\mathbb{R}^{d}\right)^{n}$ with values in $\mathbb{R}^{p}$. Asymptotic normality of $\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}$ can often be deduced from asymptotic normality of some possibly different function evaluated in the (unobservable) rescaled block maxima $\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, 1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{Z}_{r, n}$; see, for instance, Segers (2001); Bücher and Zanger (2023); Oorschot et al. (2023); Bücher and Staud (2024). In this remark, we provide some high-level conditions under which such a conclusion is possible.

As discussed in Example 2.5 below, for many functions $\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}$ of practical interest there exists a positive integer $q$ and functions $\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}:\left(\mathbb{R}^{d}\right)^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{q}, A:(0, \infty)^{d} \times \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{p \times q}$ and $B: \mathbb{R}^{d} \times(0, \infty)^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{p}$ such that

$$
\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{m}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{m}_{n}\right)=A(\boldsymbol{a}, \boldsymbol{b}) \boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(\frac{\boldsymbol{m}_{1}-\boldsymbol{b}}{\boldsymbol{a}}, \ldots, \frac{\boldsymbol{m}_{n}-\boldsymbol{b}}{\boldsymbol{a}}\right)+B(\boldsymbol{a}, \boldsymbol{b})
$$

for all $\boldsymbol{m}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{m}_{n} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$ and $\boldsymbol{b} \in \mathbb{R}^{d}, \boldsymbol{a} \in(0, \infty)^{d}$. In such a case, if we further assume that there exists a sequence $\vartheta_{r} \in \mathbb{R}^{q}$ solving the equations

$$
\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r}=A\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right) \vartheta_{r}+B\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right)
$$

(again, see below for examples), we immediately obtain that the estimation error of $\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}$ can be written as

$$
\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r}=A\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right)\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\vartheta}}_{n}-\vartheta_{r}\right)
$$

where $\hat{\boldsymbol{\vartheta}}_{n}:=\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, 1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{Z}_{r, n}\right)$ is a function of the rescaled block maxima. The difference $\hat{\boldsymbol{\vartheta}}_{n}-\vartheta_{r}$ often allows for a linearization (for instance, by the delta-method): there exist real-valued functions $h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}$ such that

$$
\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\vartheta}}_{n}-\vartheta_{r}\right)=\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}+R_{n}
$$

for some remainder $R_{n}=o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)$. Loosely spoken, if the error term $R_{n}$ is sufficiently small, the previous two displays and Theorem 2.3 imply the normal approximation

$$
\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r}=\sqrt{\frac{r}{n}} A\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right)\left(\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}+R_{n}\right) \approx_{d} \mathcal{N}_{p}\left(0, \frac{r}{n} A\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right) \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}} A\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right)^{\top}\right)
$$

where $\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}$ is the matrix from Theorem 2.3. More precisely, in the case where the matrix $A$ is invertible (in particular, $p=q$ ), we obtain the more precise result

$$
A\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right)^{-1} \sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{r}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r}\right)=\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}+o_{\mathrm{P}}(1) \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{p}\left(0, \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}\right)
$$

Example 2.5. (i) Empirical variance: consider the case $d=1$ and the empirical variance $\hat{\theta}_{n}=$ $n^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(M_{r, i}-\hat{M}_{r, n}\right)^{2}$, where $\hat{M}_{r, n}:=n^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n} M_{r, i}$, considered as an estimator for $\theta_{r}:=\operatorname{Var}\left(M_{r, 1}\right)$. In that case, (2.5) is met with $p=1, q=2, \boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(z_{1}, \ldots, z_{n}\right)=\left(\left(\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i}\right)^{2}, \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} z_{i}^{2}\right)^{\top}, B(a, b)=0$ and $A(a, b)=\left(-a^{2}, a^{2}\right)$. Moreover, $\vartheta_{r}=\left(\mathrm{E}\left[Z_{r, 1}\right]^{2}, \mathrm{E}\left[Z_{r, 1}^{2}\right]\right)^{\top}$ is a solution to (2.6) satisfying (2.8): indeed, with $h_{1}(x)=x, h_{2}(x)=x^{2}$, and using $P_{r} h_{1} \rightarrow P h_{1}$, we may write

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\vartheta}}_{n}-\vartheta_{r}\right)=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r} h_{1}\right)^{2}-\left(P_{r} h_{1}\right)^{2} \\
\mathbb{P}_{n, r} h_{2}-P_{r} h_{2}
\end{array}\right) & =\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\left(2 P h_{1}+o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)\right)\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r} h_{1}-P_{r} h_{1}\right) \\
\mathbb{P}_{n, r} h_{2}-P_{r} h_{2}
\end{array}\right) \\
& =\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}\left(\left(2 P h_{1}\right) \cdot h_{1}, h_{2}\right)^{\top}+o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)
\end{aligned}
$$

Assembling terms and solving for $\hat{\theta}_{n}-\theta_{r}$, we obtain $\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} a_{r}^{-2}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}-\theta_{r}\right)=\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}\left(h_{2}-\left(2 P h_{1}\right) \cdot h_{1}\right)+o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)$. The asymptotic variance of the limiting distribution has been explicitly calculated in Bücher and Staud (2024), see their Corollary 4.1 and Equations (C.1) and (C.2).

(ii) Probability weighted moments: consider the case $d=1$ and let $\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}: \mathbb{R}^{n} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{p}$ denote the vector containing the first $p$ empirical probability weighted moments. In that case, Equation (2.5) is met with $q=p, \boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}=\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}, A(a, b)=\operatorname{diag}(a, \ldots, a)$ and $B(a, b)=\operatorname{diag}(b, b / 2, \ldots, b /(p+1))$; see Formula (A.7) in Bücher and Zanger (2023). Moreover, Equation (2.8) can be deduced from (A.5) in that paper (for $p=3$ ), with functions $h_{1}(x)=x, h_{2}(x)=x G_{\gamma}(x)+\int_{x}^{\infty} z \mathrm{~d} G_{\gamma}(z)$ and $h_{3}(x)=$ $x G_{\gamma}^{2}(x)+2 \int_{x}^{\infty} z G_{\gamma}(z) \mathrm{d} G_{\gamma}(z)$. Finally, up to the treatment of a bias term, (2.10) corresponds to the assertion in their Theorem 3.2.
(iii) Pseudo maximum likelihood estimation in the heavy tailed case: the main steps from Remark 2.4 also apply in a slightly modified setting tailored to the heavy tailed case; details are worked out in Section 5 below.

In statistical applications, results like those in (2.9) are typically used as a starting point for inference, for instance in the form of confidence intervals for $\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}$. Routinely, such intervals would be based on normal approximations involving consistent estimators for the variances on the righthand side of those displays, which in our case requires estimation of $\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}$ and $\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}=\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[\mathrm{m}]}$. This can be a complicated task, especially for the sliding block maxima method in view of the complicated formula for the limiting variance. Alternatively, one can rely on bootstrap approximations instead of normal approximations. However, as already illustrated in the introduction, a naive approach for bootstrapping sliding block maxima fails (see also Remark 4.3 below), which prompts us to first introduce the circular block maxima method in the next section.

# 3. The circular block maxima sample 

In this section we introduce the circular block maxima method. We show that respective empirical means yield the same asymptotic variance as the sliding block maxima counterparts. The approach is interesting in its own right (particularly for computational reasons), but most importantly for this paper it suggests a straightforward bootstrap approach for bootstrapping sliding block maxima that will be discussed in Section 4.

Formally, given a sample $\mathcal{X}_{n}=\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{n}\right)$ as before, the circular block maxima sample

$$
\mathcal{M}_{i, r}^{[c]}=\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{i, 1}^{[c]}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{i, n}^{[c]}\right)
$$

is a new sample of size $n$ containing suitable block maxima that asymptotically follow the distribution $G$ in (2.2). The sample depends on two parameters: the block length parameter $r$ and an integer-valued parameter $k$ (for instance, $k=2$ or $k=3$ ) that determines the length of the interval over which we apply the circular maximum operation. Details for the univariate case are provided in Figure 2, where the sampling period $\{1, \ldots, n\}$ has been decomposed into $m(k):=m_{n}(k):=n /(k r)$ blocks of size $k r$, say $I_{k r, 1}, \ldots, I_{k r, m(k)}$ with $I_{k r, i}=\{(i-1) k r+1, \ldots, i k r\}$, and where we assume that $m(k) \in \mathbb{N}$ for simplicity. Note that every observation $X_{s}$ appears within exactly $r$ maximumoperations, and hence has the same chance to become a block maximum (this is not the case for the plain sliding block maxima sample, where, for instance, the very first observation $X_{1}$ can appear only once as sliding block maximum). This observation is in fact the main motivation for the circularization approach within each $k r$-block.

More formally, the notations used in Figure 2 are defined as follows: for a given vector $\boldsymbol{W}=$ $\left(\boldsymbol{w}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{w}_{n}\right) \in\left(\mathbb{R}^{d}\right)^{n}$ and $i \in\{1, \ldots, m(k)\}$, we let

$$
\pi_{k r, i}(\boldsymbol{W})=\left(\boldsymbol{w}_{s}\right)_{s \in I_{k r, i}}=\left(\boldsymbol{w}_{(i-1) k r+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{w}_{i k r}\right)
$$

A key feature of the circmax-sample consists of the fact that it can be stored and evaluated efficiently. More precisely, for each $k r$ block, the number of distinct circmax-values in that block is typically very small (typically around 10 for realistic block and sample sizes as observed in the simulation study); for instance, the largest observation in each block is necessarily appearing exactly $r$ times. As such, the entire circmax-sample can also be regarded as a weighted sample whose (random) size corresponds to the number of distinct values in the circmax-sample.

The following central result shows that the circmax-sample can be considered as a sample from the 'correct' limit distribution $G$ from (2.2) (a similar result on joint convergence of two circmaxobservations can be found in Proposition C. 1 of the supplement). Let

$$
Z_{r, s}^{[c]}:=\frac{\boldsymbol{M}_{r, s}^{[c]}-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}}{\boldsymbol{a}_{r}}, \quad s \in\{1, \ldots, n\}
$$

note that we suppress the dependence on $k$ for notational convenience.
Proposition 3.1 (Weak convergence of circular block maxima). Suppose that Condition 2.1 and 2.2(a) are met and that $\alpha\left(r_{n}\right) \rightarrow 0$. Then, for every fixed $k \in \mathbb{N}$ and $\xi \in[0, k)$, we have

$$
Z_{r, 1+[\xi r]}^{[c]} \rightsquigarrow Z \sim G \quad(n \rightarrow \infty)
$$

Due to Proposition 3.1, statistical methods based on the circular block maxima method may be expected to work asymptotically. As discussed in Section 2.2, a central ingredient for studying respective methods is weak convergence of empirical means. Adopting the notation from that section, we denote the empirical processes associated with the normalized sample $Z_{r, 1}^{[c]}, \ldots, Z_{r, n}^{[c]}$ by

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[c]}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[c]}-P_{n, r}^{[c]}\right), \quad \hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[c]}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[c]}-P_{r}\right), \quad \mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{[c]}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[c]}-P\right)
$$

where $\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[c]}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{s=1}^{n} \delta_{Z_{r, s}^{[c]}}, P_{n, r}^{[c]}=\frac{1}{k r} \sum_{s=1}^{k r} \mathbb{P}\left(Z_{r, s}^{[c]} \in \cdot\right), P_{r}=\mathbb{P}\left(Z_{r, 1} \in \cdot\right)$ and $P=\mathbb{P}(Z \in \cdot)$. The following result can be regarded as a circmax-counterpart of Theorem 2.3. Recall that the integrability and bias Conditions 9.1-9.3 have been postponed to Section 9 in the appendix, where we also provide an extended discussion of the bias in 9.4.

Theorem 3.2. Suppose that Conditions 2.1 and 2.2 are met. Then, for fixed $k \in \mathbb{N}_{\geq 2}$ and any finite set of real valued functions $h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}$ satisfying the integrability Condition 9.1(b) with $v>2 / \omega$, where $\omega$ is from Condition 2.2, we have $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \operatorname{Cov}\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[v]} \boldsymbol{h}\right)=\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[x]}$ and

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[v]} \boldsymbol{h} \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{q}\left(\mathbf{0}, \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[x]}\right)
$$

with $\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[x]}$ from (2.4). Moreover, if the bias Condition 9.3 holds, then

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[v]} \boldsymbol{h} \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{q}\left(\frac{D_{h, k}+E_{h}}{k}, \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[x]}\right)
$$

(with $D_{h, k}$ often equal to zero, see Remark 9.4), and if additionally the bias Condition 9.2 is met, then

$$
\mathbb{G}_{h, r}^{[v]} \boldsymbol{h} \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{q}\left(B_{\boldsymbol{h}}+\frac{D_{h, k}+E_{h}}{k}, \Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[x]}\right)
$$

The proof of Theorem 3.2 (see in particular Proposition C.1 in the supplement) shows that the sample of $k r$-blocks containing the circular block maxima can be considered asymptotically independent. This is akin to the sample of disjoint block maxima and, as discussed after Theorem 2.3, it suggests to define bootstrap versions of $\mathbb{G}_{h, r}^{[v]}$ by drawing $m(k)$-times from the sample of $k r$-blocks with replacement (which is computationally efficient: recall that all circular block maxima in a $k r$-block could be efficiently stored as a weighted sample with typically very few observations).

# 4. Bootstrapping block maxima estimators 

Throughout this section, we discuss bootstrap approximations for the empirical processes from Section 3. For completeness, we also cover the disjoint block maxima case, as it corresponds to the circular block maxima sample when $k=1$.

For fixed $k \in \mathbb{N}$, consider the circmax-sample $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[v]}$. Independent of the observations, let $\boldsymbol{W}_{m(k)}=$ $\left(W_{m(k), 1}, \ldots, W_{m(k), m(k)}\right)=\left(W_{1}, \ldots, W_{m(k)}\right)$ be multinomially distributed with $m(k)$ trials and class probabilities $\left(m(k)^{-1}, \ldots, m(k)^{-1}\right)$. Given the sample $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[v]}$, the bootstrap sample $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[v], *}$ is obtained by repeating the observations $\left(M_{n, r}^{[v]}\right)_{s \in I_{k r, i}}$ from the $i$ th $k r$-block exactly $W_{m(k), i}$-times, for every $i=$ $1, \ldots, m(k)$. The respective empirical measure of the rescaled bootstrap sample $\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, 1}^{[v], *}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{Z}_{r, n}^{[v], *}$ with $\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, 1}^{[v], *}=\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, s}^{[v], *}-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right) / \boldsymbol{a}_{r}$ can then be written as

$$
\hat{\mathbb{P}}_{n, r}^{[v], *}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{s=1}^{n} \delta_{Z_{r, s}^{[v], *}}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} W_{m(k), i} \sum_{s \in I_{k r, i}} \delta_{Z_{r, s}^{[v]}},
$$

and the associated (centered) empirical process is given by

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[v], *}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\hat{\mathbb{P}}_{n, r}^{[v], *}-\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[v]}\right)
$$

Note that the conditional distribution of $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[v], *}$ given the data $\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{n}$ can in practice be approximated to an arbitrary precision based on repeated sampling of $\boldsymbol{W}_{m(k)}$ (if $\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}$ were known; we discuss extensions below). The following result shows that the bootstrap process $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[v], *}$ provides a consistent distributional approximation for $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[v]}$ and for $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[x]}$.

Again, note that the integrability and bias conditions 9.1-9.3 referenced in the results of this section can be found in the Section 9.

Theorem 4.1 (Asymptotic validity of the circmax-resampling bootstrap). Suppose Conditions 2.1 and 2.2 are met. Then, for fixed $k \in \mathbb{N}_{2 \mid 2}$ and $\boldsymbol{h}$ satisfying the integrability Condition 9.1(b) with $v>2 / \omega$ where $\omega$ is from Condition 2.2, we have, for $\mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{s}, \mathrm{c}\}$,

$$
d_{K}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[c], *} \boldsymbol{h} \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[\mathrm{m}]} \boldsymbol{h}\right)\right)=o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)
$$

as $n \rightarrow \infty$, where $d_{K}$ denotes the Kolmogorov metric for probability measures on $\mathbb{R}^{q}$. As a consequence, if the bias Condition 9.2 is met and if $r$ is chosen sufficiently large to guarantee that $B_{h}=0$, we have

$$
d_{K}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[c], *} \boldsymbol{h} \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\mathbb{G}_{h, r}^{[s]} \boldsymbol{h}\right)\right)=o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)
$$

and if also the bias Condition 9.3 is met with $E_{h}=D_{h, k}=0$, we have

$$
d_{K}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[c], *} \boldsymbol{h} \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\mathbb{G}_{h, r}^{[c]} \boldsymbol{h}\right)\right)=o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)
$$

Remarkably, the consistency of the circmax bootstrap for the sliding block maxima method does not require the bias Condition 9.3 (nor $E_{h}=D_{h, k}=0$ in case it is met).
Remark 4.2 (Bootstrapping the disjoint block maxima empirical process). Consider the disjoint block maxima sample, whose empirical means coincide with empirical means based on the circular block maxima sample with $k=1$. The results from Theorem 4.1 continue to hold for $k=1$ ( $D_{h, k}=E_{h}=0$ is then immediate), but with 's' replaced by 'd' at all instances.
Remark 4.3 (Inconsistency of naive resampling of sliding block maxima). It seems natural to bootstrap sliding block maxima empirical means by blockwise resampling, that is, by the sliding block maxima analogue of (4.1),

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[s], *}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\hat{\mathbb{P}}_{h, r}^{[s], *}-P_{r}\right), \quad \hat{\mathbb{P}}_{h, r}^{[s], *}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{s=1}^{n} \delta_{Z_{r, s}^{[s], *}}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} W_{m(k), i} \sum_{s \in I_{k r, s}} \delta_{Z_{r, s}^{[s]}} .
$$

Note that $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[s], *}$ depends on $k$, which is suppressed from the notation. However, unlike $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[c], *}$, this process is inconsistent for both $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[s]}$ and $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[c]}$, for any $k \in \mathbb{N}$. An heuristic explanation is provided in Section D in the supplement, where we also formally prove that, considering the case $d=q=1$ for simplicity,

$$
d_{K}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[s], *} h \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right), \mathcal{N}\left(\mathbf{0}, \Sigma_{h}^{(k)}\right)\right)=o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)
$$

where $\Sigma_{h}^{(k)}=\Sigma_{h}^{[s]}-\frac{2}{k} \int_{0}^{1} \xi \operatorname{Cov}\left(h\left(Z_{1, \xi}\right), h\left(Z_{2, \xi}\right)\right) \mathrm{d} \xi$. If $\operatorname{Var}(h(Z))>0$, we have $\Sigma_{h}^{(k)}<\Sigma_{h}^{[s]}$ for any $k \in \mathbb{N}$ by Lemma C. 4 in the supplement, so in view of Theorem 3.2 the bootstrap process has a smaller asymptotic variance than needed for approximating $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[s]}$ or $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{h, r}^{[c]}$. This circumstance is one of the main motivations for working with circular block maxima.

In statistical applications, as discussed after Theorem 2.3, we do not want to bootstrap the estimation error of empirical means involving the (unobservable) $Z_{r, i}$, but the estimation error of general statistics depending on the block maxima $\boldsymbol{M}_{r, i}$ itself. We follow the general setting of Remark 2.4, that is, $\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}=\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, 1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{r, n}\right)$ is some estimator of interest for a target parameter $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$. If similar equations/linearizations as in (2.7) and (2.8) can be shown to hold for the (unobservable) circmax-bootstrap counterpart $\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[c], *}=\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(Z_{1, r}^{[c], *}, \ldots, Z_{n, r}^{[c], *}\right)$, that is, if

$$
\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[c]}=A\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{r}, \boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right)\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[c]}\right)
$$

$$
\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[c]}\right)=\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[c], *}\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}+o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)
$$

then, loosely speaking, the distributional approximation $\mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{[c]} \boldsymbol{h} \approx_{d}\left(\mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{[c], *} \boldsymbol{h} \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right)$ from Theorem 4.1 carries over to the distributional approximation $\hat{\theta}_{n}^{[c]}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r} \approx_{d}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\theta}_{n}^{[c]} \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right)$. Formally, we have the following result.

Proposition 4.4. Fix $k \in \mathbb{N}_{\geq 2}$ and assume that Conditions 2.1 and 2.2 are met. Suppose $\hat{\theta}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}=$ $\boldsymbol{\varphi}_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r, 1}^{[\mathrm{m}]}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{M}_{r, n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}\right)$ is some estimator of interest for a target parameter $\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$ such that (2.5), (2.6) and (2.8) (with $\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}=\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[\mathrm{m}]}$ ) is met for some function $\boldsymbol{h}=\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}$ satisfying the conditions of Theorem 3.2. Moreover, assume that (4.3) and (4.4) are met. Then, if $\Sigma_{\boldsymbol{h}}^{[s]}$ is invertible, for $\mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{s}, \mathrm{c}\}$,

$$
d_{K}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\theta}_{n}^{[c]} \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\hat{\theta}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}-\boldsymbol{\theta}_{r}\right)\right)=o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)
$$

The results from Proposition 4.4 are sufficient for showing that basic bootstrap confidence intervals (Davison and Hinkley, 1997) asymptotically hold their intended level. As a proof of concept, details on a specific example are given in the next section, see also Corollary A. 6 in the supplement.

# 5. Application: bootstrapping the pseudo-maximum likelihood estimator for the Fréchet distribution 

We provide details how the previous methods and results can be used for a specific important estimation problem, namely maximum likelihood estimation for parameters associated with a univariate heavy-tailed version of the MDA Condition 2.1. An extended version of this section, including formal mathematical statements and proofs, can be found in the supplement, Section A.

Condition 5.1 (Fréchet Max-Domain of Attraction). Let $\left(X_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$ denote a strictly stationary univariate time series with continuous margins. There exists some $\alpha_{0}>0$ and some sequence $\left(\sigma_{r}\right)_{r \in \mathbb{N}} \subset$ $(0, \infty)$ such that

$$
\lim _{r \rightarrow \infty} \frac{\sigma_{[r s]}}{\sigma_{r}}=s^{1 / \alpha_{0}},(s>0) \quad \text { and } \quad \frac{\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{r}\right)}{\sigma_{r}} \rightsquigarrow Z \sim P_{\alpha_{0}, 1} \quad(r \rightarrow \infty)
$$

where $P_{\alpha, \sigma}$ denotes the Fréchet-scale family on $(0, \infty)$ defined by its $\operatorname{CDF} F_{\alpha, \sigma}(x)=\exp \left(-(x / \sigma)^{-\alpha}\right)$; here $(\alpha, \sigma) \in(0, \infty)^{2}$.

Suppose $X_{1}, \ldots, X_{n}$ is an observed sample from $\left(X_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$ as in Condition 5.1, and let $r=r_{n}$ denote a block length parameter. In view of the heuristics and results from Sections 2 and 3, the associated block maxima samples $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[\mathrm{m}]}$ with $\mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{d}, \mathrm{s}, \mathrm{c}\}$ (with $k \in \mathbb{N}$ fixed) can all be considered approximate samples from $P_{\alpha_{0}, \sigma_{r}}$. As in Bücher and Segers (2018b,a), this suggests to estimate ( $\alpha_{0}, \sigma_{r}$ ) by maximizing the independence Fréchet-log-likelihood, that is, we define

$$
\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}:=\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}\right)^{\top}:=\underset{\boldsymbol{\theta}=\{\alpha, \sigma\} \in(0, \infty)^{2}}{\arg \max } \sum_{M_{i} \in \mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[\mathrm{m}]}} \ell_{\boldsymbol{\theta}}\left(M_{i} \vee \mathrm{c}\right)
$$

where, for $\boldsymbol{\theta}=(\alpha, \sigma)^{\top} \in(0, \infty)^{2}, \ell_{\boldsymbol{\theta}}(x)=\log (\alpha / \sigma)-(x / \sigma)^{-\alpha}-(\alpha+1) \log (x / \sigma)$ denotes the log density of the Fréchet distribution $P_{(\alpha, \sigma)}$ and where $c>0$ denotes an arbitrary truncation constant. As shown in the last-named references, there exists a unique maximizer of (5.1) (with probability tending to one), and the rescaled estimation error $\sqrt{n / r}\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}-\alpha_{0}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]} / \sigma_{r_{n}}-1\right)$ for both $\mathrm{m}=\mathrm{d}$ and $\mathrm{m}=\mathrm{s}$ is asymptotically normal under suitable regularity conditions.

For fixed $k \in \mathbb{N}$, consider the circmax-sample $\mathcal{M}_{n, t}^{[c]}$ and its bootstrap version $\mathcal{M}_{n, t}^{[c], *}$ as constructed in Section 4. In the supplement we show that, under suitable regularity assumption, the independence Fréchet-log-likelihood

$$
\boldsymbol{\theta} \mapsto \sum_{s=1}^{n} t_{\boldsymbol{\theta}}\left(M_{r, s}^{[c], *} \vee c\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} W_{m(k), i} \sum_{s \in \mathrm{I}_{n}, i} t_{\boldsymbol{\theta}}\left(M_{r, s}^{[c]} \vee c\right)
$$

has a unique maximimizer (with probability converging to one), say $\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *}\right)$, and that the conditional distribution of the rescaled bootstrap-estimation error, $\sqrt{n / r}\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c]}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *} / \hat{\sigma}_{n}-1\right)$, given the observations is close to the distribution of $\sqrt{n / r}\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}-\alpha_{0}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]} / \sigma_{r_{\mathrm{n}}}-1\right)$ for both $\mathrm{m} \in \mathrm{s}, \mathrm{c}$ : for $n \rightarrow \infty$, we have

$$
d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}\left(\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c]} \\
\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *} / \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}-1
\end{array}\right) \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right), \sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}-\alpha_{0} \\
\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]} / \sigma_{r_{\mathrm{n}}}-1
\end{array}\right)\right]=\mathrm{o}_{\mathrm{P}}(1)
$$

The result in the previous display allows for statistical inference on the parameters $\alpha_{0}, \sigma_{r_{\mathrm{n}}}$, for instance in the form of confidence intervals. We provide details on $\sigma_{r}$, using the circular block bootstrap approximation to the sliding block estimator: for $\beta \in(0,1)$, let $q_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}}(\beta)$ denote the $\beta$ quantile of the conditional distribution of $\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *}$ given the data, that is, $q_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}}(\beta)=\left(F_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}}\right)^{-1}(\beta)$, where $F_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}}(x)=\mathbb{P}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *} \leq x \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right)$ for $x \in \mathbb{R}$. Note that the quantile may be approximated to an arbitrary precision by repeated bootstrap sampling. Consider the following version of the basic bootstrap confidence interval (Davison and Hinkley, 1997)

$$
I_{n, \sigma}^{(\mathrm{x}, \mathrm{c})}(1-\beta)=\left[\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{x}]}+\left\{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}-q_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}}\left(1-\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\right\}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{x}]}+\left\{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}-q_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\right\}\right]
$$

Note that the interval is anchored to the sliding blocks estimator $\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{x}]}$, and that its size is controlled by quantiles of the circular blocks estimation error, $\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}$. We will show in the supplement, see Corollary A.6, that

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(\sigma_{r_{\mathrm{n}}} \in I_{n, \sigma}^{(\mathrm{x}, \mathrm{c})}(1-\beta)\right)=1-\beta
$$

and that an analogous result can be derived for the disjoint block maxima estimator. In view of the fact that the disjoint block maxima estimator exhibits a larger asymptotic estimation variance, the width of the disjoint blocks confidence interval is typically larger than the one of the slidingcircular method, for every fixed confidence level (for an empirical illustration, see Figure 23 for the related problem of providing a confidence interval for the shape parameter $\alpha$ ).

# 6. Simulation study 

The finite-sample properties of the estimators and of the bootstrap approaches have been investigated in a large scale Monte-Carlo simulation study. Two asymptotic regimes were considered: first, the case where the block size $r$ is fixed and the number of disjoint blocks is increasing which can be regarded as the most important use case for the block maxima method), and second, the case where $n$ is fixed and the block size is treated as a tuning parameter. For the sake of brevity, we only report results for the fixed block size case in the main paper; the other results are reported in the supplement.

Several target parameters associated with the law of $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}$ have been considered. In the main paper, we only report results on the univariate case and the estimation of the $(1-1 / T)$-quantile of $M_{r}$, denoted as $\operatorname{RL}(T, r)$, with $T \in\{50,100,200\}$. Note that $\operatorname{RL}(T, r)$ is a standard target parameter in

environmental extremes, as it corresponds to the $(T, r)$-return level of the underlying time series, that is, it will take on average $T$ IID disjoint blocks of size $r$ until the first such block whose maximum exceeds $\operatorname{RL}(T, r)$. In the supplement, we also present results for the expected value $\mu_{r}=\mathrm{E}\left[M_{r}\right]$ (univariate case), as well as for Spearman's rho $\rho=\rho\left(\boldsymbol{M}_{r}\right)$ (bivariate case).

Regarding return level estimation, we proceed as follows: the DoA Condition 2.1 implies that the law of $M_{r}$ is approximately GEV with location parameter $b_{r}$, scale parameter $a_{r}$ and shape parameter $\gamma$. As a consequence, $\operatorname{RL}(T, r) \approx \operatorname{RL}^{\prime}(T, r)$, where

$$
\operatorname{RL}^{\prime}(T, r)=a_{r} \frac{c_{T}^{\gamma}-1}{\gamma}+b_{r}, \quad c_{T}=-\log (1-1 / T)
$$

is the $(1-1 / T)$-quantile of the $\operatorname{GEV}\left(b_{r}, a_{r}, \gamma\right)$ distribution. This suggests the disjoint, sliding and circular block maxima estimators

$$
\hat{\mathrm{RL}}^{[m]}:=\hat{\mathrm{RL}}^{[m]}(T, r)=\hat{a}_{r}^{[m]} \frac{c_{T}^{\gamma^{[m]}}-1}{\hat{\gamma}^{[m]}}+\hat{b}_{r}^{[m]}, \quad \mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{~d}, \mathrm{~s}, \mathrm{c}\}
$$

where $\left(\hat{a}_{r}^{[m]}, \hat{b}_{r}^{[m]}, \hat{\gamma}^{[m]}\right)$ are suitable estimators obtained by fitting the GEV-distribution to the respective sample of block maxima; here, c denotes the circmax estimator with parameter $k=2$ (other choices lead to similar results). Throughout, as in Section 5, we employ (pseudo)-maximum likelihood estimation, that is,

$$
\hat{\theta}^{[m]}:=\left(\hat{a}_{r}^{[m]}, \hat{b}_{r}^{[m]}, \hat{\gamma}^{[m]}\right) \in \underset{\theta}{\arg \min } \sum_{M_{i} \in \mathcal{M}_{a r}^{[m]}} \ell_{\theta}\left(M_{i}\right)
$$

where $\ell_{\theta}$ denotes the log-likelihood function of the GEV family.
Two different classes of time series models have been employed: the first one is the ARMAX-GPD-Model, which depends on two simple parameters controlling the serial dependence and the shape parameter $\gamma$ in the DoA condition, respectively, and the second one comprises three rather specific models designed for the extreme value analysis of precipitation amounts, temperatures, and stock returns, respectively. The first class of models will be treated in this section, and the next one will be part of the next section.

The following model serves as a basis for understanding the influence of the serial dependence and the heaviness of the tail on the estimators and the bootstrap. Moreover, the finite-sample results will be used to construct a data-adaptive size-correction for the basic bootstrap confidence interval.

# 8. Conclusion 

Both the block-maxima method and the bootstrap are time-honored statistical methods that have seen wide use in applied statistics for extremes. Surprisingly, bootstrap consistency has never been proven, not even for the classical block-maxima method based on disjoint blocks. In this paper, respective consistency statements were established under high-level conditions on the datagenerating process. A new approach, called the circular block-maxima method, has been proposed to allow for valid and computationally efficient bootstrap inference regarding the sliding block maxima method. The approach may be of independent interest for extreme-value analysis of nonstationary extremes, for instance in the presence of a temporal trend. Indeed, a reasonable model assumption inspired by many applications of the disjoint block maxima method would consist of the assumption that the circular block-maxima within a fixed $k r$-block of observations, say the $i$ th one, follow an extreme-value distribution whose distribution/parameters are depending on $i$. Respective methods could be studied mathematically under a suitable triangular array structure, and we conjecture that advantages over the disjoint block maxima method will eventually show up in respective estimation variances. Other possible extensions would be the inclusion of inner-seasonal non-stationarities in the data-generating process or the generalization to empirical processes indexed by non-finite function classes. Also, a more in-depth analysis regarding a data-adapative size correction would also be an interesting possibility for future research.

## 9. Appendix: Integrability and bias conditions

In order to integrate $\boldsymbol{h}\left(Z_{r j}\right)$ to the limit, we need mild asymptotic integrability conditions. For $\mathrm{m} \in$ $\{\mathrm{d}, \mathrm{s}\}$ the condition is standard. As the circmax-sample permutates the underlying time series on a non-negligible part of the sample, we need a more involved assumption on asymptotic integrability.

In most cases both conditions can be verified by similar arguments. Note that (b) implies (a) by letting $t=r$ in the supremum. Moreover, for $k=1$ (disjoint blocks case), (a) and (b) are equivalent.

Condition 9.1 (Asymptotic Integrability). Fix $k \in \mathbb{N}$. Let $\boldsymbol{h}=\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}: \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{q}$ be an a.e. continuous function with respect to the Lebesgue-measure on $\mathbb{R}^{d}$. There exists a $v>0$ such that:
(a) $\lim \sup _{r \rightarrow \infty} \mathrm{E}\left[\left|\boldsymbol{h}\left(Z_{r, 1}\right)\right|^{2+v}\right]<\infty$.
(b) $\lim \sup _{r \rightarrow \infty} \sup _{t=1, \ldots, r} \mathrm{E}\left[\left|\boldsymbol{h}\left(\left(\max \left\{\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{t}, \boldsymbol{X}_{(k-1) r+t+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{k r}\right\}-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}\right) / \boldsymbol{a}_{r}\right)\right|^{2+v}\right]<\infty$.

The next two conditions specify the asymptotic bias resulting from the approximation of the distribution of the various block maxima of size $r_{n}$ by the extreme value distribution $G$.

Condition 9.2 (Disjoint and sliding blocks bias). Let $r=r_{n} \rightarrow \infty$ with $r_{n}=o(n)$ and let $\boldsymbol{h}=$ $\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}: \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{q}$ be measurable such that $h\left(Z_{r, 1}\right)$ and $h(Z)$ are integrable. The following limit exists:

$$
\boldsymbol{B}_{\boldsymbol{h}}=\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left\{\mathrm{E}\left[\boldsymbol{h}\left(\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, 1}\right)\right]-\mathrm{E}[\boldsymbol{h}(Z)]\right\}
$$

Circularization as applied within the cirmax-sample changes the order of observations used to calculate some of the cirular block maxima. The next conditions captures the resulting bias by decomposing it into two pieces, the first of which is due to a coupling with an independent copy $\left(\hat{X}_{t}\right)_{t}$ of $\left(X_{t}\right)_{t}$.

Condition 9.3. Let $r=r_{n} \rightarrow \infty$ with $r_{n}=o(n)$ and let $\boldsymbol{h}=\left(h_{1}, \ldots, h_{q}\right)^{\top}: \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{q}$ be measurable and $k \in \mathbb{N}_{\geq 2}$ be fixed. The following expectations and limits exist:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& D_{\boldsymbol{h}, k}=\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}} \cdot \frac{1}{r} \sum_{t=1}^{r-1} \mathrm{E}\left[\boldsymbol{h}\left(\frac{\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{t}, \boldsymbol{X}_{(k-1) r+t+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{k r}\right)-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}}{\boldsymbol{a}_{r}}\right)\right. \\
& \left.-\boldsymbol{h}\left(\frac{\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{t}, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{1}, \ldots, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{r-t}\right)-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}}{\boldsymbol{a}_{r}}\right)\right] \\
& E_{\boldsymbol{h}}=\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}} \cdot \frac{1}{r} \sum_{t=1}^{r-1} \mathrm{E}\left[\boldsymbol{h}\left(\frac{\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{t}, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{1}, \ldots, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{r-t}\right)-\boldsymbol{b}_{r}}{\boldsymbol{a}_{r}}\right)-\boldsymbol{h}\left(\boldsymbol{Z}_{r, 1}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Remark 9.4. In Theorem 3.2, the asymptotic bias of the $\widehat{\mathbb{G}}_{h}^{[c]}$-process, $D_{\boldsymbol{h}, k}+E_{\boldsymbol{h}}$, is due to the fact that the rescaled circular block maxima $\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{(k-1) r+t+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{k r}, \boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)$ with index $s=(k-$ 1) $r+1+t$ for some $t \in\{1, \ldots, r-1\}$ are not equal in distribution to a generic block maximum variable $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}$. This bias has two sources that are quantified in Condition 9.3: $D_{\boldsymbol{h}, k}$ is a measure for the average (over $t$ ) difference induced by the approximation of $\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{(k-1) r+t+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{k r}, \boldsymbol{X}_{1}, \ldots \boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)$ by $\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{(k-1) r+t+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{k r}, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{1}, \ldots, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{t}\right)$ (with $\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{t}\right)_{t}$ an independent copy of $\left(\hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{t}\right)_{t}$ ), while $E_{\boldsymbol{h}}$ is a measure for the average difference induced by the approximation of $\max \left(\boldsymbol{X}_{(k-1) r+t+1}, \ldots, \boldsymbol{X}_{k r}, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{1}, \ldots, \hat{\boldsymbol{X}}_{t}\right)$ by that of a generic block maximum variable $\boldsymbol{M}_{r}$. Note that the asymptotic bias $\boldsymbol{E}_{\boldsymbol{h}}$ already appeared in Bücher and Zanger (2023) in a slightly modified form in the setting of observing piecewisestationary time series. In Lemma C. 10 of the supplement we provide simple sufficient conditions for beta mixing time series that imply $D_{\boldsymbol{h}, k}=E_{\boldsymbol{h}}=0$.
