## A. Application: bootstrapping the pseudo-maximum likelihood estimator for the Fréchet distribution

This section is an extended version of Section 5 from the main paper. To make reading easier, the section is self-contained, with some notations from the main article being reintroduced. For instance, the following condition is Condition 5.1 from the main paper.

Condition A. 1 (Fréchet Max-Domain of Attraction). Let $\left(X_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$ denote a strictly stationary univariate time series with continuous margins. There exists some $\alpha_{0}>0$ and some sequence $\left(\sigma_{r}\right)_{r \in \mathbb{N}} \subset$ $(0, \infty)$ such that

$$
\lim _{r \rightarrow \infty} \frac{\sigma_{[r s]}}{\sigma_{r}}=s^{1 / \alpha_{0}},(s>0) \quad \text { and } \quad \frac{\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{r}\right)}{\sigma_{r}} \rightsquigarrow Z \sim P_{\alpha_{0}, 1} \quad(r \rightarrow \infty)
$$

where $P_{\alpha, \sigma}$ denotes the Fréchet-scale family on $(0, \infty)$ defined by its $\operatorname{CDF} F_{\alpha, \sigma}(x)=\exp \left(-(x / \sigma)^{-\alpha}\right)$; here $(\alpha, \sigma) \in(0, \infty)^{2}$.

Suppose $X_{1}, \ldots, X_{n}$ is an observed sample from $\left(X_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$ as in Condition A.1, and let $r=r_{n}$ denote a block length parameter. In view of the heuristics and results from Sections 2 and 3, the associated block maxima samples $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[\mathrm{m}]}$ with $\mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{d}, \mathrm{s}, \mathrm{c}\}$ (with $k \in \mathbb{N}$ fixed) can all be considered approximate samples from $P_{\alpha_{0}, \sigma_{r}}$. As in Bücher and Segers (2018b,a), this suggests to estimate ( $\alpha_{0}, \sigma_{r}$ ) by maximizing the independence Fréchet-log-likelihood, that is, we define

$$
\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}:=\left(\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}\right)^{\top}:=\underset{\boldsymbol{\theta}=\{\alpha, \sigma) \in(0, \infty)^{2}}{\arg \max } \sum_{M_{i} \in \mathcal{M}_{n i}^{[\mathrm{m}]}} \ell_{\boldsymbol{\theta}}\left(M_{i} \vee \mathrm{c}\right)
$$

where, for $\boldsymbol{\theta}=(\alpha, \sigma)^{\top} \in(0, \infty)^{2}$,

$$
t_{\theta}(x)=\log (\alpha / \sigma)-(x / \sigma)^{-\alpha}-(\alpha+1) \log (x / \sigma), \quad x>0
$$

denotes the log density of the Fréchet distribution $P_{(\alpha, \sigma)}$ and where $c>0$ denotes an arbitrary truncation constant. For the case $\mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{d}, \mathrm{s}\}$, the rescaled estimation error of $\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}$ is known to be asymptotically normal (and independent of $c$ ), that is, under suitable additional assumptions,

$$
\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\binom{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}-\alpha_{0}}{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]} / \sigma_{r_{n}}-1} \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\mu}, \Sigma^{[\mathrm{m}]}\right)
$$

for some $\boldsymbol{\mu} \in \mathbb{R}^{2}$ and some $\Sigma^{[\mathrm{m}]} \in \mathbb{R}^{2 \times 2}$ positive definite, see Bücher and Segers (2018b,a). Subsequently, we will extend these results to $\mathrm{m}=\mathrm{c}$, and we will derive a consistent bootstrap scheme for the estimation error.

For fixed $k \in \mathbb{N}$, consider the circmax-sample $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[c]}$. Independent of the observations, let $\boldsymbol{W}_{m(k)}=$ $\left(W_{m(k), 1}, \ldots, W_{m(k), m(k)}\right)=\left(W_{1}, \ldots, W_{m(k)}\right)$ be multinomially distributed with $m(k)$ trials and class probabilities $\left(m(k)^{-1}, \ldots, m(k)^{-1}\right)$. As in Section 4, conditional on $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[c]}$, the bootstrap sample $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[c], *}$ is obtained by repeating the observations $\left(M_{r, s}^{[c]}\right)_{m, l_{n}, i}$ from the $i$ th $k r$-block exactly $W_{m(k), i}$-times, for every $i=1, \ldots, m(k)$. We are going to show that the independence Fréchet-log-likelihood

$$
\boldsymbol{\theta} \mapsto \sum_{s=1}^{\mathrm{n}} t_{\theta}\left(M_{r, s}^{[c], *} \vee c\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} W_{m(k), i} \sum_{s \in l_{n}, i} t_{\theta}\left(M_{r, s}^{[c]} \vee c\right)
$$

has a unique-maximimizer (with probability converging to one), say $\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *}\right)$, and that the conditional distribution of the rescaled bootstrap-estimation error, $\sqrt{n / r}\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *},-\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c]}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *} / \hat{\sigma}_{n}-1\right)$, given the observations is close to the distribution of $\sqrt{n / r}\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}-\alpha_{0}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]} / \sigma_{r_{n}}-1\right)$ for both $\mathrm{m}=\mathrm{s}$ and $\mathrm{m}=\mathrm{c}$. We also show how this result can be used to derive valid asymptotic confidence intervals.

A couple of conditions akin to those imposed in Bücher and Segers (2018b,a) will be needed.
Condition A. 2 (All disjoint block maxima of size $\left\lfloor r_{n} / 2\right\rfloor$ diverge). For all $c>0$, the probability of the event that all disjoint block maxima of block size $\tilde{r}_{n}=\left\lfloor r_{n} / 2\right\rfloor$ are larger than $c$ converges to one.

This is Condition 2.2 in Bücher and Segers (2018a), and guarantees that the probability of the event that all (blocksize $r_{n}$ ) block maxima in $\mathcal{M}_{n, r}^{[\mathrm{m}]}$ are larger than $c$ converges to one as well, for $\mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{d}, \mathrm{s}, \mathrm{c}\}$. This will guarantee that the Fréchet-log-likelihoods under consideration are welldefined, with probability converging to one. The following condition is Condition 3.4 in Bücher and Segers (2018b); recall that $M_{r, 1}=\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{r}\right)$.

Condition A. 3 (Moments). There exists $v>2 / \omega$ with $\omega$ from Condition 2.2 such that

$$
\limsup _{r \rightarrow \infty} \mathrm{E}\left[g_{r, \alpha_{0}}\left(\left(M_{r, 1} \vee 1\right) / \sigma_{r}\right)\right]<\infty
$$

where $g_{r, \alpha_{0}}(x):=\left\{x^{-\alpha_{0}} \mathbf{1}\{x \leq e\}+\log (x) \mathbf{1}\{x>e\}\right\}^{2+v}$.
Condition A. 4 (Bias). There exists $c_{0}>0$ such that, for $j \in\{1,2,3\}$, the limits $C\left(f_{j}\right):=\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} C_{n}\left(f_{j}\right)$ and $C_{k}\left(f_{j}\right):=\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} C_{n, k}\left(f_{j}\right)$ exist, where

$$
C_{n}\left(f_{j}\right):=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(\mathrm{E}\left[f_{j}\left(\left(M_{r, 1} \vee c_{0}\right) / \sigma_{r}\right)\right]-P_{\alpha_{0}, 1} f_{j}\right)
$$

$$
C_{n, k}\left(f_{j}\right):=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left(\frac{1}{r} \sum_{s=(k-1) r+1}^{k r}\left(\mathrm{E}\left[f_{j}\left(\left(M_{r, s} \vee c_{0}\right) / \sigma_{r}\right)\right]-\mathrm{E}\left[f_{j}\left(\left(M_{r, 1} \vee c_{0}\right) / \sigma_{r}\right)\right]\right)\right)
$$

where $f_{j}:(0, \infty) \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ are defined as

$$
f_{1}(x)=x^{-a_{0}}, \quad f_{2}(x)=x^{-a_{0}} \log x, \quad f_{3}(x)=\log x
$$

The first part of this condition on $C_{n}$ is Condition 3.5 in Bücher and Segers (2018b), and provides control of the bias for those block maxima which are calculated based on $r$ successive observations. For the circmax-sample, the last $r$ observations in a $k r$-block of that sample are not of that form; their contribution to the bias is controlled by the condition on $C_{n, k}$.

Subsequently, we fix a truncation constant $c>0$, and we write

$$
\mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{[c]}=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left(\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[c]}-P_{\left(\alpha_{0}, 1\right)}\right), \quad \hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n}^{[c], *}=\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left(\hat{\mathbb{P}}_{n, r}^{[c], *}-\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[c]}\right)
$$

where

$$
\mathbb{P}_{n, r}^{[c]}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{s=1}^{n} \delta_{\left(M_{r}^{[c]} \vee c\right) / \sigma_{r}}, \quad \hat{\mathbb{P}}_{n, r}^{[c], *}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} W_{m(k), i} \sum_{s \in I_{k r, i}} \delta_{\left(M_{r}^{[c]} \vee c\right) / \sigma_{r}}
$$

the double use of notation with (3.1) and (4.1) should not cause any confusion. Furthermore, we suppress the dependence on $c$ in the notation, which is motivated by the fact that the limiting distribution does not depend on $c$, as shown in the following theorem.

Theorem A.5. Fix $k \in \mathbb{N}_{\geq 2}$ and $c>0$, and suppose that Conditions 2.2 and A.1-A. 4 are satisfied. Then, with probability tending to one, there exists a unique maximizer $\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c]}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}\right)$ of the Fréchet log-likelihood $\boldsymbol{\theta} \mapsto \sum_{i=1}^{n} \ell_{\theta}\left(M_{r, s}^{[c]} \vee c\right)$, and this maximizer satisfies

$$
\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left(\frac{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c]}-\alpha_{0}}{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]} / \sigma_{r_{n}}-1}\right)=M\left(\alpha_{0}\right) \mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{[c]}\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}\right)^{\top}+o_{\mathrm{F}}(1) \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{2}\left(M\left(\alpha_{0}\right)\left(C+k^{-1} C_{k}\right), \Sigma^{[\mathrm{s}]}\right)
$$

where $\mathbf{C}=\left(C\left(f_{1}\right), C\left(f_{2}\right), C\left(f_{3}\right)\right)^{\top}, \mathbf{C}_{k}=\left(C_{k}\left(f_{1}\right), C_{k}\left(f_{2}\right), C_{k}\left(f_{3}\right)\right)^{\top}$ and

$$
M\left(\alpha_{0}\right)=\frac{6}{\pi^{2}}\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\alpha_{0}^{2} & \alpha_{0}(1-\gamma) & -\alpha_{0}^{2} \\
\gamma-1 & -\left(\Gamma^{\prime \prime}(2)+1\right) / \alpha_{0} & 1-\gamma
\end{array}\right), \quad \Sigma^{[\mathrm{s}]}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0.4946 \alpha_{0}^{2} & -0.3236 \\
-0.3236 & 0.9578 \alpha_{0}^{-2}
\end{array}\right)
$$

with $\Gamma(z)=\int_{0}^{\infty} t^{z-1} e^{-t} d t$ the Euler Gamma function and $\gamma=0.5772 \ldots$ the Euler-Mascheroni constant.
Moreover, also with probability tending to one, there exists a unique maximizer $\left(\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}, \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *}\right)$ of $\theta \mapsto \sum_{s=1}^{n} \ell_{\theta}\left(M_{r, s}^{[c], *} \vee c\right)$, and this maximizer satisfies

$$
\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left(\frac{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c]}}{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *} / \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}-1}\right)=M\left(\alpha_{0}\right) \hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[c], *}\left(f_{1}, f_{2}, f_{3}\right)^{\top}+o_{\mathrm{F}}(1) \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{2}\left(0, \Sigma^{[\mathrm{s}]}\right)
$$

Fix $\mathrm{m} \in\{\mathrm{s}, \mathrm{c}\}$. If $r_{n}$ is chosen sufficiently large such that, for $j \in\{1,2,3\}, C\left(f_{j}\right)=0(\mathrm{~m}=\mathrm{s})$ or $C\left(f_{j}\right)=C_{k}\left(f_{j}\right)=0(\mathrm{~m}=\mathrm{c})$ in Condition A.4, we have bootstrap consistency in the following sense:

$$
d_{\mathrm{E}}\left[\mathbf{L}\left(\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left(\frac{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], *}-\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c]}}{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], *} / \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}-1}\right) \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right), \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}}\left(\frac{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]}-\alpha_{0}}{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[\mathrm{m}]} / \sigma_{r_{n}}-1}\right)\right]=o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)
$$

The result in Theorem A. 5 allows for statistical inference on the parameters $\alpha_{0}, \sigma_{r}$, for instance in the form of confidence intervals. We provide details on $\sigma_{r}$, using the circular block bootstrap approximation to the sliding block estimator: for $\beta \in(0,1)$, let $q_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], v}}(\beta)$ denote the $\beta$-quantile of the conditional distribution of $\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], v}$ given the data, that is, $q_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], v}}(\beta)=\left(F_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], v}}\right)^{-1}(\beta)$, where $F_{\hat{\alpha}_{n}^{[c], v}}(x)=$ $\mathbb{P}\left(\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], v} \leq x \mid \mathcal{X}_{n}\right)$ for $x \in \mathbb{R}$. Note that the quantile may be approximated to an arbitrary precision by repeated bootstrap sampling. Consider the basic bootstrap confidence interval (Davison and Hinkley, 1997)

$$
I_{n, \sigma}^{[x, c]}(1-\beta)=\left[\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[x]}+\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}-q_{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], v}}\left(1-\frac{\beta}{2}\right), \hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}+\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c]}-q_{\hat{\sigma}_{n}^{[c], v}}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\right]
$$

Corollary A.6. Under the conditions of Theorem A. 5 with $r_{n}$ chosen sufficiently large such that, for $j \in\{1,2,3\}, C\left(f_{j}\right)=0$ in Condition A.4, we have, for any $\beta \in(0,1)$,

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \mathbb{P}\left(\sigma_{r_{n}} \in I_{n, \sigma}^{[x, c]}(1-\beta)\right)=1-\beta
$$

The above result only concerns the sliding block maxima estimator, but an analogous result can be derived for the disjoint block maxima estimator and under additional bias conditions for the circmax estimator. In view of the fact that the disjoint block maxima estimator exhibits a larger asymptotic estimation variance, the width of the disjoint blocks confidence interval is typically larger than the one of the circmax method, for every fixed confidence level (for an empirical illustration, see Figure 23 for the related problem of providing a confidence interval for the shape parameter $\gamma$ ).

# B. Proofs 

Proof of Theorem 2.3. The proof is a simplified version of our proof of Theorem 3.2 below, whence we omit further details. Under slightly different conditions, a proof can be found in Theorem B. 1 in Bücher and Zanger (2023) or Theorem 8.7 in Bücher and Staud (2024).

Proof of Theorem 3.2. Throughout, we omit the upper index [c]. We start by showing that

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \operatorname{Cov}\left(\overline{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r} \boldsymbol{h}\right)=\Sigma_{\mathbf{h}}^{[x]}
$$

By elementary arguments, it is sufficient to consider the case $q=1$. For $i \in\{1, \ldots, m(k)\}$ write

$$
D_{n, i}=\frac{1}{k r} \sum_{s \in I_{n, i}}\left\{h\left(\mathcal{Z}_{r, s}\right)-\mathrm{E}\left[h\left(\mathcal{Z}_{r, s}\right)\right]\right\}
$$

such that $\overline{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r} h_{j}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} m(k)^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} D_{n, i}$. By stationarity and $n / r=k m(k)$, we have

$$
\operatorname{Var}\left(\overline{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r} h\right)=k \operatorname{Var}\left(D_{n, 1}\right)+r_{n 1}+r_{n 2}
$$

where $r_{n 1}=2 k\left(1-\frac{1}{m(k)}\right) \operatorname{Cov}\left(D_{n, 1}, D_{n, 2}\right)$ and $r_{n 2}=2 k \sum_{d=2}^{m(k)-1}\left(1-\frac{d}{m(k)}\right) \operatorname{Cov}\left(D_{n, 1}, D_{n, 1+d}\right)$. Thus, the proof of (B.1) is finished once we show that

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} k \operatorname{Var}\left(D_{n, 1}\right)=\Sigma_{\mathrm{h}}^{[x]}, \quad \lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} r_{n 1}=0, \quad \lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} r_{n 2}=0
$$

We start with the former, and for that purpose we define, for $\xi, \xi^{\prime} \in[0, k)$,

$$
f_{r}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right):=\operatorname{Cov}\left(h\left(\mathcal{Z}_{r, 1+[\tau \xi]}\right), h\left(\mathcal{Z}_{r, 1+\left[\tau \xi^{\prime}\right]}\right)\right)
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) & :=\operatorname{Cov}\left(h\left(Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|,(k)}^{(1)}\right), h\left(Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|,(k)}^{(2)}\right)\right) \\
g\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) & :=\operatorname{Cov}\left(h\left(Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}^{(1)}\right), h\left(Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}^{(2)}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\left(Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|,(k)}^{(1)}, Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|,(k)}^{(2)}\right)$ has $\operatorname{CDF} G_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}^{(k)}$ from (C.1) and where $\left(Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}^{(1)}, Z_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}^{(2)}\right)$ has $\operatorname{CDF} G_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}$ from (2.3). Observe that, by Proposition C.1, Condition 9.1 and Example 2.21 in van der Vaart (1998), $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} f_{r}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right)=g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right)$. Hence, by Condition 9.1 and Dominated Convergence

$$
\begin{aligned}
k \operatorname{Var}\left(D_{n, 1}\right)=\frac{1}{k r^{2}} \sum_{s=1}^{k r} \sum_{t=1}^{k r} \operatorname{Cov}\left[h\left(Z_{r, s}\right), h\left(Z_{r, t}\right)\right] & =\frac{1}{k} \int_{0}^{k} \int_{0}^{k} f_{r}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi \\
& =\frac{1}{k} \int_{0}^{k} \int_{0}^{k} g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi+o(1)
\end{aligned}
$$

Now let $u(x):=g(x, 0)$ and note that $g\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right)=u\left(\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|\right)$ and that $u(x)=0$ for $x>1$. By the definition of $G_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}^{(k)}$ in (C.1) we have $G_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}^{(k)}=G_{\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|}$ if $0 \leq\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right| \leq k-1$, which also implies that $g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right)=g_{(k)}\left(\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|, 0\right)=g\left(\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|, 0\right)=u\left(\left|\xi-\xi^{\prime}\right|\right)$ for $\xi \leq k-1$. Therefore,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{0}^{k} \int_{\xi}^{k} g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi & =\int_{0}^{k} \int_{\xi}^{k \wedge(\xi+k-1)} u\left(\xi^{\prime}-\xi\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi+\int_{0}^{1} \int_{\xi+k-1}^{k} g_{(k)}\left(\xi^{\prime}-\xi, 0\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi \\
& =\int_{0}^{k} \int_{\xi}^{k \wedge(\xi+1)} u\left(\xi^{\prime}-\xi\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi+\int_{0}^{1} \int_{k-1+\xi}^{k} g_{(k)}\left(\xi^{\prime}-\xi, 0\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi
\end{aligned}
$$

where we used that $u(x)=0$ for $x>1$ at the second equality. After substituting $x=\xi^{\prime}-\xi$ in the inner integral and noting that $\int_{0}^{1} u(x) \mathrm{d} x=\Sigma_{h}^{[x]} / 2$, the first integral on the right-hand side of (B.6) can be written as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\int_{0}^{k} \int_{\xi}^{k \wedge(\xi+1)} u\left(\xi^{\prime}-\xi\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi=\int_{0}^{k} \int_{0}^{(k-\xi) \wedge 1} u(x) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} \xi & =\int_{0}^{k-1} \int_{0}^{1} u(x) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} \xi+\int_{k-1}^{k} \int_{0}^{k-\xi} u(x) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} \xi \\
& =(k-1) \frac{\Sigma_{h}^{[x]}}{2}+\int_{0}^{1} \int_{0}^{y} u(x) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} y
\end{aligned}
$$

where we used the substitution $y=k-\xi$ in the last step. Moreover, substituting $x=k-\xi^{\prime}+\xi$ in the inner integral, the second integral on the right-hand side of (B.6) can be written as

$$
\int_{0}^{1} \int_{k-1+\xi}^{k} g_{(k)}\left(\xi^{\prime}-\xi, 0\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi=\int_{0}^{1} \int_{\xi}^{1} g_{(k)}(k-x, 0) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} \xi=\int_{0}^{1} \int_{\xi}^{1} u(x) \mathrm{d} x \mathrm{~d} \xi
$$

where we used that $g_{(k)}(k-x, 0)=u(x)$ for $x \in[0,1]$ by the definition of $G_{k-x}^{(k)}$. Overall, again using that $\int_{0}^{1} u(x) \mathrm{d} x=\Sigma_{h}^{[x]} / 2$, the previous three displays imply that

$$
\int_{0}^{k} \int_{\xi}^{k} g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi=k \frac{\Sigma_{h}^{[x]}}{2}
$$

This implies (B.4) in view of the symmetry $\int_{0}^{k} \int_{\xi}^{k} g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi=\int_{0}^{k} \int_{0}^{\xi} g_{(k)}\left(\xi, \xi^{\prime}\right) \mathrm{d} \xi^{\prime} \mathrm{d} \xi$ and (B.5).
Similar arguments as before, invoking asymptotic independence of $Z_{r, s}$ and $Z_{r, t}$ for $s \in I_{k r, 1}$ and $t \in I_{k r, 2}$ (see Proposition C.1) and a similar identification of the covariances as integrals, imply that $r_{n 1}=o(1)$. Finally, by Conditions 2.2(c) and 9.1 and Lemma 3.11 in Dehling and Philipp (2002) we obtain

$$
\frac{\left|r_{n 2}\right|}{k} \lesssim m(k) \alpha(k r)^{v /(2+v)} \lesssim\left(\left(\frac{n}{r}\right)^{1+2 / v} \alpha(k r)\right)^{v /(2+v)}=o(1)
$$

since $2 / \omega<\nu$, where we have used that there is a lag of at least $k r$ between the observations making up $D_{n, 1}$ and $D_{n, 1+d}$. Overall, we have shown all three assertions in (B.4), and hence the proof of (B.1) is finished.

To verify the asymptotic normality, by the Cramér-Wold Theorem, it is again sufficient consider the case $q=1$. Recalling that $\tilde{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r} h$ is centered, the case $\Sigma_{h}^{[x]}=0$ follows from (B.1); thus assume $\Sigma_{h}^{[x]}>0$. Following Bücher and Segers (2018a), we use a suitable blocking technique. Choose $m^{*}=$ $m_{n}^{*} \in \mathbb{N}$ with $3 \leq m^{*} \leq m(k)$ such that $m^{*} \rightarrow \infty$ and $m^{*}=o\left((n / r)^{\nu /(2(1+\nu))}\right)$ with $v$ from Condition 9.1. Next, define $p:=p_{n}:=m(k) / m^{*}$ and assume for simplicity that $p \in \mathbb{N}, n / r \in \mathbb{N}$. Furthermore, let $J_{j}^{+}:=\left\{(j-1) m^{*}+1, \ldots, j m^{*}-1\right\}, J_{j}^{-}:=\left\{j m^{*}\right\}$ and note that $\left|J_{j}^{+}\right|=\left(m^{*}-1\right)$. Then,

$$
\tilde{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r} h=\frac{1}{\sqrt{p}} \sum_{j=1}^{p}\left(S_{n, j}^{+}+S_{n, j}^{-}\right), \quad \text { where } \quad S_{n, j}^{+}:=\sqrt{\frac{n p}{r}} \frac{1}{m(k)} \sum_{i \in J_{j}^{+}} D_{n, i}
$$

with $D_{n, i}$ from (B.2). Noticing that the time series $\left(S_{n, j}^{-}\right)_{j}$ is stationary, we have

$$
\operatorname{Var}\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{p}} \sum_{j=1}^{p} S_{n, j}^{-}\right) \leq 3 \operatorname{Var}\left(S_{n, 1}^{-}\right)+\sum_{d=2}^{p-1}\left|\operatorname{Cov}\left(S_{n, 1}^{-}, S_{n, 1+d}^{-}\right)\right|=: r_{n 3}+r_{n 4}
$$

By Conditions 2.2(a) and 9.1 we have $r_{n 3}=O\left(1 / m^{*}\right)=o(1)$. Furthermore, by Condition 9.1 and Lemma 3.11 from Dehling and Philipp (2002) with $s=r=1 /(2+v)$ and $t=v /(2+v)$, we have $\sup _{d \geq 2}\left|\operatorname{Cov}\left(S_{n, 1}^{-}, S_{n, 1+d}^{-}\right)\right| \lesssim 10 k\left(m^{*}\right)^{-1} \alpha^{v /(2+\nu)}(k r)$, whence $r_{n 4} \lesssim r^{-1} n\left(m^{*}\right)^{-2} \alpha^{v /(2+\nu)}(k r)=$ $o\left(\left(m^{*}\right)^{-2}\right)=o(1)$ by Condition 2.2 and the fact that $2 / v<\omega$. Put together, in view of $\mathrm{E}\left[S_{n, j}^{-}\right]=0$, these convergences imply $p^{-1 / 2} \sum_{j=1}^{p} S_{n, j}^{-}=o_{\mathrm{P}}(1)$.

As there is a lag of at least $k r$ between the observations making up $S_{n, j_{1}}^{+}$and $S_{n, j_{2}}^{-}$for $j_{1} \neq j_{2}$ a standard argument involving characteristic functions, a complex-valued version of Lemma 3.9 in Dehling and Philipp (2002), Condition 2.2 (b) and Levy's Continuity Theorem allows for assuming that the $\left(S_{n, j}^{+}\right)_{j}$ are independent. Hence, we may subsequently apply Lyapunov's central limit theorem. To verify its conditions, note that, since $\operatorname{Var}\left(p^{-1 / 2} \sum_{j=1}^{p} S_{n, j}^{-}\right)=o(1)$ and by using (B.1) and (B.7), $\operatorname{Var}\left(p^{-1 / 2} \sum_{j=1}^{p} S_{n, j}^{+}\right)=\operatorname{Var}\left(\tilde{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r} h\right)+o(1)=\Sigma_{h}^{[x]}+o(1)$. Hence,

$$
\frac{\sum_{j=1}^{p} \mathrm{E}\left[\left|S_{n, j}^{+}\right|^{2+\nu}\right]}{\left\{\operatorname{Var}\left(\sum_{j=1}^{p} S_{n, j}^{+}\right)\right\}^{1+\nu / 2}} \lesssim \frac{p(n p / r)^{1+\nu / 2}\left(m^{*} / m(k)\right)^{2+\nu}}{\left(p \sigma^{2} / 2\right)^{1+\nu / 2}} \lesssim \frac{\left(m^{*}\right)^{1+\nu}}{(n / r)^{\nu / 2}}=o(1)
$$

by Condition 9.1 and the choice of $m^{*}$. An application of Lyapunov's central limit theorem implies the assertion.

To prove the additional weak convergences note that

$$
\tilde{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[c]} h=\tilde{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[c]} h+\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(P_{n, r}^{[c]}-P_{r}\right) h, \quad \mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{[c]} h=\tilde{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[c]} h+\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(P_{n, r}^{[c]}-P_{r}+P_{r}-P\right) h
$$

Denote by $\left(\tilde{X}_{t}\right)_{t}$ an independent copy of $\left(X_{t}\right)_{t}$. By stationarity we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(P_{n, r}^{[c]}-P_{r}\right) h= & \frac{1}{m(k)} \sum_{t=1}^{m(k)} \frac{1}{k r} \sum_{s=1}^{k r} \mathrm{E}\left[h\left(Z_{r,(t-1) k r+s}\right)\right]-P_{r} h \\
& =\frac{1}{k r} \sum_{s=(k-1) r+2}^{k r}\left(\mathrm{E}\left[h\left(Z_{r, s}\right)\right]-P_{r} h\right) \\
& =\frac{1}{k r} \sum_{t=1}^{r-1} \mathrm{E}\left[h\left(\frac{\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{t}, X_{(k-1) r+t+1}, \ldots, X_{k r}\right)-b_{r}}{a_{r}}\right)-h\left(\frac{\boldsymbol{M}_{r, 1}-b_{r}}{a_{r}}\right)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Condition 9.3 then gives $\sqrt{n / r}\left(P_{n, r}^{[c]}-P_{r}\right) h \rightarrow k^{-1}\left(D_{h, k}+E_{h}\right)$. Furthermore, Condition 9.2 immediately implies $\sqrt{n / r}\left(P_{r}-P\right) h \rightarrow B_{h}$. Combined with the first assertion and the penultimate display, we obtain the additional two claimed weak convergences.

Proof of Theorem 4.1. The second and third assertion follow immediately from the first one and the triangular inequality. For the proof of the first one, we omit the upper index c. By Theorem 2.3 (for $\mathrm{m}=\mathrm{s}$ ) or Theorem 3.2 (for $\mathrm{m}=\mathrm{c}$ ) and Lemma 2.3 from Bücher and Kojadinovic (2019), it is sufficient to show that, unconditionally,

$$
\left(\hat{G}_{n, r}^{[1]} \boldsymbol{h}, \hat{G}_{n, r}^{[2]} \boldsymbol{h}\right) \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{q}\left(\mathbf{0}, \Sigma_{h}^{[s]}\right) \otimes \mathcal{N}_{q}\left(\mathbf{0}, \Sigma_{h}^{[s]}\right)
$$

where, for $b \in\{1,2\}, \hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}^{[b]}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left(W_{m(k), i}^{[b]}-1\right) \sum_{s \in I_{n, r}} \delta_{\mathrm{Z}_{i, s}}$ with $\boldsymbol{W}_{m(k)}^{[b]}=\left(W_{m(k), 1}^{[b]}, \ldots, W_{m(k), m(k)}^{[b]}\right)$ two i.i.d. copies of $\boldsymbol{W}_{m(k)}$. By the Cramér-Wold device, it is sufficient to consider $q=1$, and for this in turn, yet again by the Cramér-Wold device, it is sufficient to show that

$$
T_{n}:=\sum_{b=1}^{2} a_{b} \sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left(W_{m(k), i}^{[b]}-1\right) \sum_{s \in I_{n, r}} h\left(Z_{r, s}\right) \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}_{2}\left(0,\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}\right) \Sigma_{h}^{[s]}\right)
$$

for all $\boldsymbol{a}=\left(a_{1}, a_{2}\right)^{\top} \in \mathbb{R}^{2}$. Note that $\sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left(W_{m(k), i}^{[b]}-1\right)=0$ and that $\sum_{s \in I_{n, r}} \mathrm{E}\left[h\left(Z_{r, s}\right)\right]$ does not depend on $i$, whence we may write

$$
\begin{aligned}
T_{n} & =\sum_{b=1}^{2} a_{b} \sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left(W_{m(k), i}^{[b]}-1\right)\left\{\sum_{s \in I_{n, r}} h\left(Z_{r, s}\right)-\mathrm{E}\left[h\left(Z_{r, s}\right)\right]\right\} \\
& =\sum_{b=1}^{2} a_{b} \sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \frac{1}{m(k)} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left(W_{m(k), i}^{[b]}-1\right) D_{n, i}
\end{aligned}
$$

with $D_{n, i}$ from (B.2). The subsequent proof strategy, known as Poissonization, consists of removing the dependence of the multinomial multipliers by introducing rowwise i.i.d. multiplier sequences that approximate the multinomial multipliers. More precisely, we employ the construction from Lemma C.3: for each fixed $n \in \mathbb{N}$, let $\left(\boldsymbol{U}_{j, m(k)}^{[b]}\right)_{j \in \mathbb{N}, b \in\{1,2\}}$ be i.i.d. multinomial vectors with 1 trial and $m(k)$ classes, with class probabilities $1 / m(k)$ for each class, and independent of $\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$. We may then assume that

$$
\boldsymbol{W}_{m(k)}^{[b]}=\sum_{j=1}^{m(k)} \boldsymbol{U}_{j, m(k)}^{[b]}
$$

Further, independent of $\left(\boldsymbol{U}_{j, m(k)}^{[b]}\right)_{j \in \mathbb{N}, b \in\{1, \ldots, 2\}}$ and of $\left(\boldsymbol{X}_{t}\right)_{t \in \mathbb{Z}}$, let $\left(N_{m(k)}^{[b]}\right)_{b=1, \ldots, M}$ be i.i.d. Poisson $(m(k))$ distributed random variables. Define

$$
\hat{\boldsymbol{W}}_{m(k)}^{[b]}=\left(\hat{W}_{m(k), 1}^{[b]}, \ldots, \hat{W}_{m(k), m(k)}^{[b]}\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{N_{m(k)}^{[b]}} \boldsymbol{U}_{j, m(k)}^{[b]}
$$

By Lemma C. 3 the random vectors $\hat{\boldsymbol{W}}_{m(k)}^{[1]}, \hat{\boldsymbol{W}}_{m(k)}^{[2]}$ are i.i.d. Poisson $(1)^{\otimes m(k)}$ distributed. Then, in view of (B.9), we may write $T_{n}=\tilde{T}_{n}+a_{1} R_{n 1}+a_{2} R_{n 2}$, where

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \tilde{T}_{n}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \frac{1}{m(k)} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left\{\sum_{b=1}^{2} a_{b}\left(\hat{W}_{m(k), i}^{[b]}-1\right)\right\} D_{n, i} \\
& R_{n b}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \frac{1}{m(k)} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left(W_{m(k), i}^{[b]}-\hat{W}_{m(k), i}^{[b]}\right) D_{n, i}
\end{aligned}
$$

We may apply Lemma C. 2 to obtain that $\tilde{T}_{n} \rightsquigarrow \mathcal{N}\left(0,\left(a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}\right) \Sigma_{0}^{[\mathrm{s}]}\right)$. For the proof of (B.8), it hence remains to verify that $R_{n b}=o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)$ for $b \in\{1,2\}$. We will suppress the upper index $[b]$ in the following. First write

$$
R_{n b}=\sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \frac{1}{m(k)} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} D_{n, i} \operatorname{sgn}\left(N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right) \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} \mathbf{1}\left(i \in I_{m(k)}^{j}\right)
$$

where $I_{m(k)}^{j}=\left\{i \in\{1, \ldots, m(k)\}:\left|\tilde{W}_{m(k), i}-W_{m(k), i}\right| \geq j\right\}$.
We will start by showing that $\mathbb{P}\left(A_{n}\right)=o(1)$, where $A_{n}:=\left\{\left|I_{m(k)}^{3}\right|>0\right\}=\{\mathfrak{2} \in\{1, \ldots, m(k)\}:$ $\left|\tilde{W}_{m(k), i}-W_{m(k), i}\right| \geq 3\}$. Fix $\delta>0$. Invoking the central limit theorem, we may choose $C=C_{\delta}>0$ sufficiently large such that $\mathbb{P}\left(\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right|>C \sqrt{m(k)}\right) \leq \delta$ for all $n \in \mathbb{N}$. Next, note that, conditional on $N_{m(k)}=M$, the difference $\left|\tilde{W}_{m(k), i}-W_{m(k), i}\right|$ follows a $\operatorname{Bin}\left(|M-m(k)|, m(k)^{-1}\right)$ distribution. Further, setting $c=\left\lceil C \sqrt{m(k)}\right\rceil$ and choosing $M$ such that $|M-m(k)| \leq c$, we have that $\operatorname{Bin}\left(|M-m(k)|, m(k)^{-1}\right)\left(\left[3,|M-m(k)|\right]\right) \leq \operatorname{Bin}\left(c, m(k)^{-1}\right)([3, c])$. As a consequence, conditioning on the event $N_{m(k)}=M$, we obtain

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathbb{P}\left(A_{n}\right) & \leq \mathbb{P}\left(\left|I_{m(k)}^{3}\right|>0,\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right| \leq c\right)+\delta \\
& \leq \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} \mathbb{P}\left(\left|\tilde{W}_{m(k), i}-W_{m(k), i}\right| \geq 3,\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right| \leq c\right)+\delta \\
& \leq m(k) \operatorname{Bin}\left(c, m(k)^{-1}\right)([3, c])+\delta \\
& \leq m(k)\left(c m(k)^{-2}+\operatorname{Poisson}\left(c m(k)^{-1}\right)([3, c])\right)+\delta \\
& =\frac{c}{m(k)}+m(k) e^{-c / m(k)} \sum_{j=3}^{c} \frac{\left(c m(k)^{-1}\right)^{j}}{j!}+\delta \\
& =O\left((m(k))^{-1 / 2}\right)+\delta
\end{aligned}
$$

where we used the approximation error of the Poisson Limit Theorem. Hence, since $\delta>0$ was arbitrary, $\mathbb{P}\left(A_{n}\right)=o(1)$.

Next, note that, on $A_{n}^{c}$,

$$
\left|I_{m(k)}^{1}\right|+\left|I_{m(k)}^{2}\right|=\sum_{j=1}^{\infty}\left|I_{m(k)}^{j}\right|=\sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} \sum_{j=1}^{\infty} \mathbf{1}\left(i \in I_{m(k)}^{j}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{m(k)}\left|\tilde{W}_{m(k), i}-W_{m(k), i}\right|=\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right|
$$

using the fact that $\boldsymbol{U}_{j, m(k)}$ is multinomially distributed with 1 trial. As a consequence, letting $H_{n, i}=$ $\mathbf{1}\left(N_{m(k)} \neq m(k)\right)\left[\mathbf{1}\left(i \in I_{m(k)}^{1}\right)+\mathbf{1}\left(i \in I_{m(k)}^{2}\right)\right] /\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right|$ and $\tilde{R}_{n b}=\left|\sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} H_{n, i} D_{n, i}\right|$, we obtain that

$$
\left|R_{n b}\right| \leq \mathbf{1}_{A_{n}^{c}}\left|\sqrt{\frac{\pi}{r}} \frac{1}{m(k)} \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} D_{n, i} \sum_{j=1}^{2} \mathbf{1}\left(i \in I_{m(k)}^{j}\right)\right|+o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)=\mathbf{1}_{A_{n}^{c}} \sqrt{k} \times \frac{\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right|}{\sqrt{m(k)}} \times \tilde{R}_{n b}+o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)
$$

Therefore, since $\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right| / \sqrt{m(k)}=O_{\mathrm{F}}(1)$ by the Central Limit Theorem, the proof of (B.8) is finished if we show that $\tilde{R}_{n b}=o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)$. For that purpose note that, for any fixed $\varepsilon>0$,

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(\frac{\mathbf{1}\left(N_{m(k)} \neq m(k)\right)}{\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right|} \geq \varepsilon\right) \leq \mathbb{P}\left(\left|N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right| \leq \frac{1}{\varepsilon}\right)=o(1)
$$

by the Central Limit Theorem, which in turn yields $\max _{i=1, \ldots, m(k)} H_{n, i} \leq 2\left|\left(N_{m(k)}-m(k)\right)\right|^{-1} \mathbf{1}\left\{N_{m(k)} \neq\right.$ $m(k)\}=o_{\mathrm{F}}(1)$.

Now let $\sigma_{r}(i, j)=\operatorname{Cov}\left(D_{n, i}, D_{n, j}\right)$ and invoke the Conditional Tschebyscheff inequality to obtain that, for fixed $\varepsilon>0$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{P}\left(\left|\tilde{R}_{n b}\right|>\varepsilon \mid\left(H_{n, i}\right)_{i=1, \ldots, m(k)}\right) \\
& \lesssim \sum_{i, j=1}^{m(k)} H_{n, i} H_{n, j}\left|\sigma_{r}(i, j)\right| \\
& \leq\left\{\max _{j=1}^{m(k)} H_{n, j}\right\} \times\left\{\sum_{i=1}^{m(k)} H_{n, i} \sigma_{r}(1,1)+2 \sum_{i=1}^{m(k)-1} H_{n, i}\left|\sigma_{r}(1,2)\right|+\sum_{|i-j| \geq 2} H_{n, i}\left|\sigma_{r}(i, j)\right|\right\} \\
& \leq\left\{\max _{j=1}^{m(k)} H_{n, j}\right\} \times\left\{\sigma_{r}(1,1)+2\left|\sigma_{r}(1,2)\right|+2 m(k) \max _{d=2}^{m(k)-1}\left|\sigma_{r}(1,1+d)\right|\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

# C.2. Auxiliary results on bootstrap consistency 

Lemma C.8. Let $S_{n}, T_{n} \in \mathbb{R}^{q}$ with $S_{n} \rightsquigarrow S, T_{n} \rightsquigarrow S \in \mathbb{R}^{q}$. Furthermore, let $\mathcal{L}(S)$ be absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure on $\mathbb{R}^{q}$. We then have

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n} S_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n} T_{n}\right)\right]=0
$$

for any sequence $\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n}\right)_{n} \subset \mathbb{R}^{p \times q}$ of matrices.
Proof. Write $\boldsymbol{A}_{n}=\left(\boldsymbol{a}_{n, j}^{\top}\right)_{j=1, \ldots, p}$ with $\boldsymbol{a}_{n, j} \in \mathbb{R}^{q}$. A straightforward argument shows that we may assume $\boldsymbol{a}_{n, j} \neq \mathbf{0}$ for all $j=1, \ldots p$. Next, note that, for all diagonal matrices $\boldsymbol{D}=\operatorname{diag}\left(d_{j}\right)_{j=1, \ldots, p}$ with $d_{j} \neq 0$ and all $\mathbb{R}^{p}$-valued random variables $S, T$, we have $d_{K}[\mathcal{L}(S), \mathcal{L}(T)]=d_{K}[\mathcal{L}(D S), \mathcal{L}(D T)]$. Hence, letting $d_{j}:=\left\{\boldsymbol{a}_{n, j}\right\}_{2}^{-1}$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n}=\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{a}}_{n, j}^{\top}\right)_{j=1, \ldots, p}$ with normed $\tilde{a}_{n, j}=\boldsymbol{a}_{n, j} /\left\{\boldsymbol{a}_{n, j}\right\}_{2} \in \mathbb{R}^{p}$, we have $\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n}=\boldsymbol{D} \boldsymbol{A}_{n}$ and therefore

$$
d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n} S_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n} T_{n}\right)\right]=d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n} S_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n} T_{n}\right)\right]
$$

Since $\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n} \in[-1,1]^{p \times q}$, the Bolzano-Weierstraß Theorem allows to find a subsequence $n^{\prime}:=n^{\prime}(n)$ such that $\boldsymbol{E}=\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} \tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n^{\prime}}$ exists. Slutsky's lemma then yields the weak convergences $\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n^{\prime}} S_{n^{\prime}} \rightsquigarrow E S$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n^{\prime}} T_{n^{\prime}} \rightsquigarrow E S$. We will show below that the CDF of $E S$ is continuous. Since the Kolmogorovmetric $d_{K}$ metrizes weak convergence to limits with continuous CDFs (van der Vaart, 1998, Lemma 2.11), an application of the triangular inequality implies

$$
d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n^{\prime}} S_{n^{\prime}}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n^{\prime}} T_{n^{\prime}}\right)\right] \leq d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n^{\prime}} S_{n^{\prime}}\right), \mathcal{L}(E S)\right]+d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}(E S), \mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n^{\prime}} T_{n^{\prime}}\right)\right]=o(1)
$$

for $n^{\prime} \rightarrow \infty$. As the previous argumentation can be repeated for subsequences $n^{\prime}$ of arbitrary subsequences $n^{\prime \prime}$, we then have $d_{K}\left[\mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n} S_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n} T_{n}\right)\right]=o(1)$, which implies the assertion by (C.12).

It remains to show that the CDF of $E S$ is continuous. For that purpose, by Sklar's theorem and the fact that copulas are continuous, it is sufficient to show that each marginal CDF of $E S$ is continuous. Hence, fix $j \in\{1, \ldots, p\}$, and note that the $j$ th row of $\boldsymbol{E}$, say $\boldsymbol{e}_{j}^{\top}$, has Euclidean norm 1. We may therefore construct an invertible matrix $\tilde{\boldsymbol{E}}=\tilde{\boldsymbol{E}}\left(\boldsymbol{e}_{j}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{q \times q}$ with the first row of $\tilde{\boldsymbol{E}}$ being equal to $\boldsymbol{e}_{j}^{\top}$. Then $\tilde{\boldsymbol{E}}$ being a diffeomorphism and $S$ being absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesguemeasure on $\mathbb{R}^{q}$ implies the latter for $\tilde{E} S$. Hence, for any $y \in \mathbb{R}, \mathbb{P}\left((E S)_{j}=y\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(\tilde{E} S \in\{y\} \times \mathbb{R}^{q-1}\right)=0$. Since $y \in \mathbb{R}$ was arbitrary, this proves the continuity of $y \mapsto \mathbb{P}\left((E S)_{j} \leq y\right)$.

Lemma C.9. Let $(\Omega, \mathcal{A}, \mathbb{P})$ denote a probability space and $p, q \in \mathbb{N}$. For $n \in \mathbb{N}$, let $X_{n}: \Omega \rightarrow$ $\mathcal{X}_{n}, W_{n}: \Omega \rightarrow W_{n}$ denote random variables in some measurable space $\mathcal{X}_{n}, W_{n}$, respectively. (a) $d_{\infty}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(S_{n}^{*} \mid X_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(S_{n}\right)\right) \xrightarrow{\mathcal{V}} 0, \quad$ as $n \rightarrow \infty$;

$$
\text { (b) } \quad S_{n} \rightsquigarrow Q, \quad \text { as } n \rightarrow \infty \text {; }
$$

where $Q$ is absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue-measure on $\mathbb{R}^{q}$ and $d_{w}$ denotes any metric characterizing weak convergence on $\mathbb{R}^{q}$; then

$$
d_{K}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n} S_{n}^{*} \mid \boldsymbol{X}_{n}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n} S_{n}\right)\right) \xrightarrow{\mathrm{P}} 0, \quad \text { as } n \rightarrow \infty

Proof. Let $n^{\prime} \subset \mathbb{N}$ denote a subsequence of $\mathbb{N}$. By assumption (a), we may choose a further subsequence $n^{\prime \prime}$ of $n^{\prime}$ and $\Omega_{0} \in \mathcal{A}$ with $\mathbb{P}\left(\Omega_{0}\right)=1$ such that

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} d_{w}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(S_{n^{\prime \prime}}^{*} \mid \boldsymbol{X}_{n^{\prime \prime}}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(S_{n^{\prime \prime}}\right)\right)=0 \quad \text { on } \Omega_{0}
$$

Hence, since $S_{n} \rightsquigarrow Q$ by assumption, we obtain $\mathcal{L}\left(S_{n^{\prime \prime}}^{*} \mid \boldsymbol{X}_{n^{\prime \prime}}\right) \rightsquigarrow Q$ on $\Omega_{0}$. Lemma C. 8 then implies

$$
\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} d_{K}\left(\mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n^{\prime \prime}} S_{n^{\prime \prime}}^{*} \mid \boldsymbol{X}_{n^{\prime \prime}}\right), \mathcal{L}\left(\boldsymbol{A}_{n^{\prime \prime}} S_{n^{\prime \prime}}\right)\right)=0 \quad \text { on } \Omega_{0}
$$

which lets us conclude.

\begin{aligned}
R_{n} & =\sup _{t=r / 2, \ldots, r} \sqrt{\frac{n}{r}} \underset{j=1}{d}\left\{\mathbb{P}\left(\max \left(X_{t-t+1, j}, \ldots, X_{t, j}\right)>\max \left(X_{1, j}, \ldots, X_{t-t, j}, X_{t+1, j}, \ldots, X_{r, j}\right)\right)\right\}^{\frac{1+r}{2+r}} \\
& =o(1)
\end{aligned}
$$

Subsequently, we write $X_{i}$ instead of $X_{t-j}$, as all subsequent bounds are uniform in $j$. We then have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathbb{P}\left(\max \left(X_{t-t+1}, \ldots, X_{t}\right)>\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{t-t}, X_{t+1}, \ldots, X_{r}\right)\right) \\
\leq & \sum_{i=t-t+1}^{t} \mathbb{P}\left(X_{i}>\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{t-t}, X_{t+1}, \ldots, X_{r}\right)\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

For fixed $i$ in the previous sum, let $J \subset\{1, \ldots, t-\ell\}$ denote the maximal set of indexes such that $\left|j_{1}-i\right| \geq \ell$ and $\left|j_{1}-j_{2}\right| \geq \ell$ for all distinct $j_{1}, j_{2} \in J$; note that $|J|=O(r / \ell)$ since $t>r / 2$. We then have

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(X_{i}>\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{t-\ell}, X_{t+1}, \ldots, X_{r}\right)\right) \leq \mathbb{P}\left(X_{i}>\max \left(X_{j}: j \in J\right)\right)
$$

We may now successively apply Berbee's coupling lemma (Berbee, 1979) to construct a vector $\left(\hat{X}_{j}\right)_{j \in J}$ with iid coordinates that is independent of $X_{i}$ and satisfies $\hat{X}_{j}=_{d} X_{j}$ for all $j \in J$ such that

$$
\mathbb{P}\left(X_{i}>\max \left(X_{s}: s \in J\right)\right) \leq \mathbb{P}\left(X_{i}>\max \left(\hat{X}_{s}: s \in J\right)\right)+|J| \beta(t)
$$

More precisely, writing $J=\left\{j_{1}, \ldots, j_{|J|}\right\}$, the first application is to $X_{j_{1}}$ and $\left(X_{j_{2}}, \ldots, X_{j_{j_{1}}}, X_{i}\right)$. The second application is to $\left(\hat{X}_{j_{1}}, X_{j_{2}}\right)$ and $\left(X_{j_{3}}, \ldots, X_{j_{j_{1}}}, X_{i}\right)$, where $\hat{X}_{j_{i}}$ is the random variable constructed with the first application, and so on.

Since $\mathbb{P}\left(X_{i}>\max \left(\hat{X}_{s}: s \in J\right)\right)=2^{-|J|}$ by Fubini's theorem, we obtain from the last three displays that

$$
\sup _{t=r / 2, \ldots, r} \mathbb{P}\left(\max \left(X_{t-\ell+1}, \ldots, X_{t}\right)>\max \left(X_{1}, \ldots, X_{t-\ell}, X_{t+1}, \ldots, X_{r}\right)\right) \leq \ell 2^{-|J|}+\ell|J| \beta(r) \lesssim \ell 2^{-r / \ell}+r \lambda^{\ell}
$$

In view of our choice of $\ell=\left[r^{1 / 2}\right]$, and letting $\zeta=\min (2,1 / \lambda)>1$, the right hand side is bounded by $2 r \zeta^{-\sqrt{r}}$, whence $R_{n}$ from (C.19) can be bounded by

$$
R_{n} \lesssim \sqrt{\frac{n}{r}}\left(r \zeta^{-\sqrt{r}}\right)^{(1+v) /(2+v)}=\exp \left\{-\sqrt{r}\left(\log (\zeta) \frac{1+v}{2+v}-\frac{\log r}{\sqrt{r}} \frac{1+v}{2+v}-\frac{\log (n / r)}{\sqrt{r}}\right)\right\}=o(1)
$$

by assumption on $r$. This proves (C.19), and the proof is finished.

# D. Resampling sliding block maxima vs. resampling circular block maxima 

In this section, we provide an intuitive heuristic for the inconsistency of naive resampling of sliding block maxima and explain why the method of resampling circular block maxima solves the problem. We thereby extend the brief discussion in the introduction and in Remark 4.3 from the main article. At the end of this section, we formally prove the statements made in Remark 4.3.

For simplicity, assume $m=m(2)=n /(2 r) \in \mathbb{N}$, and write $I_{i}=I_{2 r, i}=\{(i-1) 2 r+1, \ldots, 2 r i\}$ for the $i$ th disjoint block of size $2 r$. We are interested in the affinely standardized empirical mean

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[s]}(h)=\sqrt{n / r}\left\{\frac{1}{n} \sum_{s=1}^{n} h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[s]}\right)-\mathrm{E}\left[h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[s]}\right)\right]\right\}=\sqrt{n / r} \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{m} D_{n, i}^{[s]}
$$

and in its naive sliding and circular blocks bootstrap analogs

$$
\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[s], s}(h)=\sqrt{n / r} \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{m} Y_{n, i} D_{n, i}, \quad \hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[s], s}(h)=\sqrt{n / r} \frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{m} Y_{n, i} D_{n, i}^{[s]} ;
$$

here, $D_{n, j}^{[s]}=(2 r)^{-1} \sum_{s \in I_{i}} h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[s]}\right)-\mathrm{E}\left[h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[s]}\right)\right], D_{n, i}^{[v]}=(2 r)^{-1} \sum_{s \in I_{i}} h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[v]}\right)-\mathrm{E}\left[h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[v]}\right)\right]$ and $\left(Y_{n, i}\right)_{i}$ are iid multipliers with expectation 0 and variance 1 . Writing $\sigma_{r}(s, t)=\operatorname{Cov}\left(h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[s]}\right), h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[s]}\right)\right)$, the variance of $\mathbb{G}_{n, r}^{[s]}(h)$ can be written as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\mathbb{G}}_{n, r}^{[s]}(h)\right)=\frac{1}{n r} \operatorname{Var}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{m} \sum_{s \in I_{i}} h\left(Z_{r, s}^{[s]}\right)\right) & =\frac{1}{n r} \sum_{i, j=1}^{m} \sum_{s \in I_{i}} \sum_{t \in I_{j}} \sigma_{r}(s, t) \\
& =\frac{1}{n r} \sum_{i=1}^{m} \sum_{s \in I_{i}} \sum_{t=s-r+1}^{s+r-1} \sigma_{r}(s, t) \\
& =\frac{1}{2 r^{2}} \sum_{s=1}^{2 r} \sum_{t=s-r+1}^{s+r-1} \sigma_{r}(s, t)
\end{aligned}
$$

where, at the $\approx$-sign, we have used asymptotic independence of two sliding block maxima in case their respective index sets do not overlap and where, for the ease of notation, we have extended the available sample by $r$ observations at the beginning and the end of the sampling period of length $n$ (which does not matter asymptotically). Moreover, we used stationarity at the last equation. The index set of the double sum in the last line, say $B_{r}$, is illustrated in green in the left panel of Figure 12.

Next, since $\left(\Upsilon_{n, t} D_{n, i}\right)$; is uncorrelated, we have

$$
\operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}^{[s], v}(h)\right)=\frac{n}{m r} \operatorname{Var}\left(D_{n, 1}\right)=\frac{1}{2 r^{2}} \sum_{s=1}^{2 r} \sum_{t=1}^{2 r} \sigma_{r}(s, t) \approx \frac{1}{2 r^{2}} \sum_{(s, t) \in D_{r}} \sigma_{r}(s, t)
$$

where

$$
D_{r}=\left\{(s, t) \in\{1, \ldots, 2 r\}^{2}:|s-t| \leq r\right\}
$$

and where we have again used asymptotic independence of two sliding block maxima in case their respective index sets do not overlap (at the $\approx$-sign); see the middle panel of Figure 12 for an illustration of the index set $D_{r}$. Compared to (D.1), we observe that the summands with index $(s, t) \in B_{r}$ such that either $t>2 r$ or $t \leq 0$ are missing in (D.2). This makes a significant difference asymptotically, and ultimately yields inconsisteny of the naive sliding blocks approach.

For the circ-max approach, writing $\sigma_{r}^{(c)}(s, t):=\operatorname{Cov}\left(h\left(Z_{r, s}^{(c)}\right), h\left(Z_{r, t}^{(c)}\right)\right)$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}^{(c), v}(h)\right)=\frac{n}{m r} \operatorname{Var}\left(D_{n, 1}^{(c)}\right) & =\frac{1}{2 r^{2}} \sum_{s=1}^{2 r} \sum_{t=1}^{2 r} \sigma_{r}^{(c)}(s, t) \\
& =\frac{1}{2 r^{2}}\left(\sum_{(s, t) \in D_{r}}+\sum_{(s, t) \in E_{r}^{+}}+\sum_{(s, t) \in E_{r}^{-}}\right) \sigma_{r}^{(c)}(s, t)
\end{aligned}
$$

where

$$
\begin{aligned}
& E_{r}^{+}=\left\{(s, t) \in\{1, \ldots, 2 r\}^{2}: s-t>r\right\} \\
& E_{r}^{-}=\{(s, t) \in\{1, \ldots, 2 r\}^{2}: t-s>r\}
\end{aligned}
$$

see the blue sets in the right panel in Figure 12. Now, by Proposition C.1 and stationarity,

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma_{r}^{(c)}(s, t) & =\sigma_{r}(0,|s-t|) & =\sigma_{r}(s, t) & & \text { if }(s, t) \in D_{r} \\
\sigma_{r}^{(c)}(s, t) & =\sigma_{r}(0,2 r-(s-t)) & =\sigma_{r}(s, 2 r+t) & & \text { if }(s, t) \in E_{r}^{+} \\
\sigma_{r}^{(c)}(s, t) & =\sigma_{r}(0,2 r-(t-s)) & =\sigma_{r}(s, t-2 r) & & \text { if }(s, t) \in E_{r}^{-}
\end{aligned}
$$

As a consequence, we can match the blue triangles in Figure 12 with the red ones by an index shift:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{Var}\left(\hat{\mathrm{G}}_{n, r}^{(c)}(f)\right) & =\frac{1}{2 r^{2}}\left\{\sum_{(s, t) \in D_{r}} \sigma_{r}(s, t)+\sum_{(s, t) \in E_{r}^{+}} \sigma_{r}(s, 2 r+t)+\sum_{(s, t) \in E_{r}^{-}} \sigma_{r}(s, t-2 r)\right\} \\
& =\frac{1}{2 r^{2}}\left\{\sum_{(s, t) \in D_{r}} \sigma_{r}(s, t)+\sum_{(s, t) \in E_{r}^{+}} \sigma_{r}(s, t)+\sum_{(s, t) \in E_{r}^{-}} \sigma_{r}(s, t)\right\} \\
& =\frac{1}{2 r^{2}} \sum_{s=1}^{2 r} \sum_{t=s-r+1}^{s+r-1} \sigma_{r}(s, t)
\end{aligned}
$$

This is the same expression as in (D.1), and heuristically explains consistency of the circmaxapproach.

# F.4. Runtime comparison 

In classical situations, the computational cost of the bootstrap depends linearly on the number of bootstrap replications and is therefore high if a single evaluation of a statistic of interest is computationally intensive. Since both the sliding and the circular block maxima samples are much larger than the plain disjoint block maxima sample (sample sizes $n$ vs. $n / r$, respectively), one may naively think that the former methods require substantially more computational resources. As we will argue below and prove with simulations, this naive heuristic is not correct.

For any block maxima method, the starting point for a single evaluation of a statistic of interest is the calculation of the respective block maxima samples, which requires evaluating $O(n / r)$ maxima for the disjoint block maxima method, or $O(n)$ maxima for the sliding and circular block maxima method. Subsequently, when the statistic of interest is applied to one of the samples, the fact that both the sliding and the circmax samples can be efficiently stored as a weighted sample of size $O(n / r)$ implies that the additional computational cost of the latter two methods is, approximately,

Next, for the bootstrap approaches proposed within this paper, no additional evaluation of maxima is ever required, whence, overall, the only major difference between the three approaches is the initial calculation of the block maxima samples. Therefore, the relative computational effort should only depend on $n$, and only moderately.

The disjoint blocks method has been considered as a benchmark, whence we depict relative runtimes with respect to that method. We find that, as expected, the relative runtime is mostly depending on $n$, with only a moderate loss in performance for the circmax-method. Similar results were obtained for other estimators and models.

abstract:
The block maxima method is a standard approach for analyzing the extremal
behavior of a potentially multivariate time series. It has recently been found
that the classical approach based on disjoint block maxima may be universally
improved by considering sliding block maxima instead. However, the asymptotic
variance formula for estimators based on sliding block maxima involves an
integral over the covariance of a certain family of multivariate extreme value
distributions, which makes its estimation, and inference in general, an
intricate problem. As an alternative, one may rely on bootstrap approximations:
we show that naive block-bootstrap approaches from time series analysis are
inconsistent even in i.i.d.\ situations, and provide a consistent alternative
based on resampling circular block maxima. As a by-product, we show consistency
of the classical resampling bootstrap for disjoint block maxima, and that
estimators based on circular block maxima have the same asymptotic variance as
their sliding block maxima counterparts. The finite sample properties are
illustrated by Monte Carlo experiments, and the methods are demonstrated by a
case study of precipitation extremes.
